> > > > > 1.(sometimes initial capital letter) a governmental system led =
by
> a
> > > > > dictator having complete power, forcibly suppressing =

> > > > > concerns.  So in some sense terrorist and fascist are mutually

Back about 10-12 years ago, I owned a company called DIVE Labs that develop=
ed virtual reality technology for simulations, entertainment, and business =
applications.  During a trade show in NYC, I met a former stripper who call=
ed herself Skye London.  She was intereseted in developing "full body conta=
ct" virtual reality sex simulations for a club she had recently opened in N=
ew York.  So I went over to the club to check it out.  Essentially it was w=
hat Chester has described here.  Everyone was naked or almost so.  The prob=
lem was that other than the dancers (one of whom was Skye's 18-19 year old =
daughter) there wasn't anyone in the place that you wanted to see naked.

I was concerned about liability issues with full body contact interfaces in=
 public places, so I declined to build that aspect.  But I did present a bi=
d for stereoscopic video projection and production equipment.  I think she =
had expected me to want to do this for free after seeing the club, or maybe=
 after having sex with her and her daughter, because I never heard from her=
 again after that.

Anyway, the point is that an "all naked party" is in the realm of be carefu=
l what you wish for becasue you might actually get it.  And what you'll get=
 is a bunch of fat old men in leather speedos.

Peace,

Peter

[yet alone FOUR] on a STAGE is generally a VERY bad idea.  How many times do

concept?  I mean, christ!  If I had a dollar for each time I've played on a

-->  DON'T set up turntables on a stage if you haven't properly sound tested
or adjusted for FEEDBACK!  Ok.  Got that off my chest.

Another community list I was on on had this very problem of too much
politically-infused discussion amidst the topics at hand - so they
created a separate politics list for those community members who just
couldn't stop on the subject, hence sheltering other members from
banter that might be un-interesting to them.

However, the sphere of what encompassed political discussion became so
wide that I couldn't even post a link to an environmental commentary,
so I got fed up and left the list altogether.

Anyway, maybe a group of you who like talking politics could consider
this in some form or fashion.

~Jenn~

DJ Assault/DJ Funk coming to MIGHTY!

Date & Time: 	Friday, September 8, 2006 more on this date
10:00 PM
BIG SMILE & EGGS
along with Rollerdisco
present

GET: OH!!!

with
DJ FUNK
DJ ASSAULT
DJ JEFRODISIAC (frisco disco)
SAFETY SCISSORS (proptronix, eggs)
MONSIEUR M (seventh heaven)
PEEPLAY (deejaypeeplay.com)
DESTROY ALL GENRES (west add radio)

In the Gallery:
Man VS Machine
w/
THE BASTARD PRINCE (handsome boy/ rondo bros)
OONCEOONCE (tigerbeat6, west add radio)
MOPHONO (dj centipede)
YOKO SOLO (quake trap)

Mighty
119 Utah st
$3 drink specialities
lmtd $8 .adv tix at mighty119.com

Tear the club up, Tear the F**king club up!

After his first 2006 visit to San Francisco, DJ FUNK comes back with
a bigger, better, faster, stronger team to make you work it.
September 8th, Mighty will be turned out into a booty bass banquet,
featuring the accelerated funk of DJ ASSAULT, with ghetto-tech
support by the best electro and booty bass DJs to make you percolate.

SF has been bringing back the booty of yore. No, not booty as in the
bootleg mash-up party, but the original booty bass, ghetto tech, juke
house, 808, 909, sweaty crowds, dirty synths, nasty lyrics and lots
of bounce. July saw FUNK's first round with San Francisco as well as
DJ GODFATHER's descent from Detroit. It seems that the bay area, now
quite good at getting hyphy and going dumb, wants to shake dat ass, too.

DJ FUNK had the crowd at BLOW-UP ripping clothes off, screaming and
wanting more. He's back and ready to face Mighty's soundsystem. His
high speed ghetto house selections spin at pitches unheard, his
pornographic tracks violate your romantic house anthems, and his
electricity will seep through your pores. Expect jams like "Booty
Bounce," "Perk-U-Lated," "Pop that Pussy," and more.

DJ ASSAULT, "The Street Narrator" straight from Detroit has packed
international dancefloors, striking audiences with his classic hit,
"Ass n Titties." He's been making the most popular and infectious
booty-bass tracks ever produced. His hooks and brilliant transitions
make arousal inevitable. Expect tracks like "I See Booty," "Fuck You
Hoe," "Big Booty Bitch," and more.

Even if its chilly out, this night will be hot, and your ass will be
on fire. Sure, it's offensive, but damn it's fun.

> 119 Utah st
> $3 drink specialities
> lmtd $8 .adv tix at mighty119.com
> 
> Tear the club up, Tear the F**king club up!
> 
> After his first 2006 visit to San Francisco, DJ FUNK comes back with
> a bigger, better, faster, stronger team to make you work it.
> September 8th, Mighty will be turned out into a booty bass banquet,
> featuring the accelerated funk of DJ ASSAULT, with ghetto-tech
> support by the best electro and booty bass DJs to make you percolate.
> 
> SF has been bringing back the booty of yore. No, not booty as in the
> bootleg mash-up party, but the original booty bass, ghetto tech, juke
> house, 808, 909, sweaty crowds, dirty synths, nasty lyrics and lots
> of bounce. July saw FUNK's first round with San Francisco as well as
> DJ GODFATHER's descent from Detroit. It seems that the bay area, now
> quite good at getting hyphy and going dumb, wants to shake dat ass, too.
> 
> DJ FUNK had the crowd at BLOW-UP ripping clothes off, screaming and
> wanting more. He's back and ready to face Mighty's soundsystem. His
> high speed ghetto house selections spin at pitches unheard, his
> pornographic tracks violate your romantic house anthems, and his
> electricity will seep through your pores. Expect jams like "Booty
> Bounce," "Perk-U-Lated," "Pop that Pussy," and more.
> 
> DJ ASSAULT, "The Street Narrator" straight from Detroit has packed
> international dancefloors, striking audiences with his classic hit,
> "Ass n Titties." He's been making the most popular and infectious
> booty-bass tracks ever produced. His hooks and brilliant transitions
> make arousal inevitable. Expect tracks like "I See Booty," "Fuck You
> Hoe," "Big Booty Bitch," and more.
> 
> Even if its chilly out, this night will be hot, and your ass will be
> on fire. Sure, it's offensive, but damn it's fun.

Ravers seize 10 million house

31.08.06 


Revellers are flocking to this house in north London.

Squatters have seized a 10 million home to host drug-fuelled raves, it has emerged.

Furious residents of the exclusive Primrose Hill area of North London say their lives have been made a nightmare since the eight bedroom house was taken over two months ago. 

The occupants charge hundreds of ravers 5 each to attend all-night parties which shatter the peace of the area that is home to celebrities including David Walliams, Gwen Stefani, Sadie Frost and Jamie Oliver.

The front of the house is littered with beer cans, broken glass and used needles, while inside the carpets have been ripped up and the walls covered in graffiti.

But despite scores of complaints, police say they are powerless to act until the owner of the property gets a court order to evict the revellers. 

The squatters boast that the only thing the police have done is to politely ask them to keep the noise down.

The takeover comes amid a resurgence in illegal rave parties, fuelled by confusion over the Government's reclassification of drugs and pocket money prices for substances.

Kitty Massey, whose home backs on to the garden of the occupied house, said the scale of the raves was 'unimaginable'.

'Hundreds of screaming teenagers are turning up in droves and heavy metal and rock music has been blasting out day and night.

Subject: [sfraves] If you're not going to raves, WTF are you doing then?

I only make it to raves or parties every couple months, I end up going
to more shows or bars/clubs for techno acts. Going back to school and
working full-time takes a lot out of me, not to mention the drive from
the northbay.

it would be narrow-minded to ignore any of the great talent that is
pouring through SF right now just because it isn't in a warehouse
w/bad ventiliation.

Is everyone else just lurking or are they  living vicariously through
those of us who go out? Whats your excuse? DELURK and ANSWER! :)

Since the birth of my son (who will be turning 1 in a couple of weeks), i'd
have to demote myself and live vicariously through others.

I wish it could be otherwise, but babies are expensive, and i tend to spend
what little money i do get on strippers and beer.  My nights and weekends
are shot because that's when momma has to work and go to school.

So all of you remember when you're drinking your 40 to pour a little out for
your downed homie!!!

Subject: [sfraves] Deep Min Tek + Microhouse @ Club Six on Fri. Sept 8

Deep Mix @ Club Six (in the Dark Room)
With ::solekandi:. and special guest from Microphono's Minneaplis
James Patrick (3 + hour DJ set)

Friday, September 8
9 PM - 4 AM
Club Six's Dark Room (Right next to Club Six. Look for the Deep Mix signs)

60 6th St.(btw Market + Mission)
San Francisco, CA.
10 PM to 4 AM
$5 to $10

www.babd.org

Headlining Deep Mix @ Club Six Friday, September 8 is
Minneapolis-based techno figurehead, producer and DJ James Patrick,
who is at the forefront of the new minimal, micro-house and tech-house
movement in the US.

His passion for pushing dance music's often worn envelope has turned
MNPLS, MN. Into the new American headquarters for electronic dance
music's third wave.

Come see, feel and hear why: www.microphono.com/jamespatrick

Bay Area Beatdr_p's favorite JP set:
www.secrettechno.com/jamespatrick ( in the folder titled "geologic").

"JP spearheaded a DIY movement that's giving Minneapolis quite the ego
boost. No longer is it the sulking middle child next to Chicago and
Detroit. The attention is coming from the Twin Cities' version of
microhouse, the most unlikely sound--or perhaps the most cyclically
logical--to derive from over-the-top rave culture's entrails."
(Source: The Minneapolis/St Paul City Pages "Microhouse goes Macro at
the Dinkytowner," June 15, 2005)

More information at: www.babd.org and solekandi.com
============================================================
Details:

We're going till 4:00 a.m. in Club Six's Dark Room with Minneapolis's
James Patrick, whom many of us agree is one of the best underground
Techno Djs in the US today.

A 5-hour mix we heard online a few months back sent Yanni and I on a
wild goose chase for JP and since then, we've been inspired by his
work. It's raw, deep, emotive, spellbinding and innovative...crossing
from house to tech to experimental. In short, he sure to join the
ranks of other favorites like Bruno Pronsato and John Tejada, leading
the 3rd wave for techno on our own shores.

Look for JP's upcoming releases on New York's www.microcosm-music.com
and Philly's www.unfoundsoundrecords.com that are sure to reshape any
preconceived notions of techno.

Read more about James Patrick:

http://www.iprschool.com/newsletter/issue2_07_05/article_13.asp

http://citypages.com/databank/26/1280/article13412.asp

More links to JP projects:

www.secrettechno.com
www.microphono.com
www.klikmusik.com
www.vitalvinyl.com/category/minimal.aspx
www.iprschool.com
http://www.spark.cla.umn.edu/

Subject: [sfraves] BT: This Binary Universe CD/DVD Review

Well it is a mini review seeing how I have not gotten through the whole 
thing. But man BT is a music master. The CD is more Film Score style so it 
is not dance music what so ever. More ambient downtempo-ish. Good shit the 
First two movies on the series are a bit freaky and acidic (sp) Trippy 
visual display. The 3 I like alot are 1.618 Nice cinematic style vid and 
track. The anhtkythera mecanism because it has people in the vid very good 
work. And last but not least is Good morning Kaia a tribute to his daughter 
freakin awesome sound and video work on that one, my favorite by far out of 
them all.

BT keeps suprising me with each new record release a musician among 
musicians!!!

If you have the means I say pick it up, but keep in mind it is not a dance 
album, but more a collection of songs and short movie clips.


Macadio

Subject: Re: [sfraves] If you're not going to raves, WTF are you doing  then?

Oh man.  I am sad to hear this Apollo.  FWIW, your postings have always and continue to mean a lot to me and others on this list. 

I remember NYE a couple of years back I was at Arc in NYC.  Sander Kleinenberg was spinning.  My wife and I met this couple, Danny and I forget the girls name.  Danny was in a wheelchair and was paralyzed from the waist down.  He was wheeling that chair all over the place and popping wheelies. He had a huge smile on his face.  In fact I think he was the happiest guy in the place. His spirit was unbroken and I saw that anything was possible that night.  I know  I'll never ever forget him.

I hope you will get back to on the dance floor somehow or other.  I want to be there when it happens.

Regards,

Peter

Subject: Re: [sfraves] has SFR lost relevance?

This is what I've seen happen over time.

First, we had BBS's.  They ruled.
Then came the net, now we're all connected if you were in college.  ;)
Then came the web.  The masses discovered Email.
Lists were where it's at.  All content delivered to your desktop.
Then came forums.  Every site now had it's own BBS.  Lots and lots of 
accounts to create (we're still in this inane cycle)
Now you have what I refer to as BBS 4.0:  Tribe, MySpace, Free Ass, 
Tagworld, Friendster, etc.  Of these, Tribe & MySpace are the most 
useful, Tribe being moreso because of the BBS capabilities there are 
part of the basic structure.

Will things migrate back to lists?  Who knows.  Consumers constantly 
flip flop between the Mega Stores and boutiwue specialty shops.  Think 
of Sears, Wards, JC Penny in the 60-70's, the rise of the Mall Shop in 
the 80's ad 90's and now the flop back to mega stores- eg Costco, 
Walmart, Target, etc.

Trends change, things evolve and advance.  Nothing stays stagnant or it 
dies.

I'm waiting for everything to go 100% mobile tied into the various 
things.  Simple submission, filters for what you care about, Auto date 
book, text sms, tied into desktop as well.  Things auto updateing via 
WiFi or cell so that when you decide you want to go do something, and 
based on what your filter criteria are, you can get on your mobile 
device a list of club, event, underground, etc etc.

Stuff like RSS is leading toward this in a big way, I'm just waiting for 
some crazy uber geek to take all these unrelated emerging techs to 
intergrate into the next system.

However, I think lists will slowly wither, especially when you could 
easily migrate to something like tribe, set up a private tribe, talk as 
we do here about whatever, all nicely threaded, platform independent.  
Get everything here plus anything else you are into on a personal 
level.  With Tribe you can also subscribe to a tribe via RSS so you 
could watch your groups while using your fave email program at work or 
what have you.

ok...  now I'm just geek rambling.  ;)

--S

At 05:16 PM 9/1/2006, Shatter wrote:
>This is what I've seen happen over time.
>
>First, we had BBS's.  They ruled.
>Then came the net, now we're all connected if you were in college.  ;)
>Then came the web.  The masses discovered Email.
>Lists were where it's at.  All content delivered to your desktop.
>Then came forums.  Every site now had it's own BBS.  Lots and lots 
>of accounts to create (we're still in this inane cycle)
>Now you have what I refer to as BBS 4.0:  Tribe, MySpace, Free Ass, 
>Tagworld, Friendster, etc.  Of these, Tribe & MySpace are the most 
>useful, Tribe being moreso because of the BBS capabilities there are 
>part of the basic structure.
>
>Will things migrate back to lists?  Who knows.  Consumers constantly 
>flip flop between the Mega Stores and boutiwue specialty 
>shops.  Think of Sears, Wards, JC Penny in the 60-70's, the rise of 
>the Mall Shop in the 80's ad 90's and now the flop back to mega 
>stores- eg Costco, Walmart, Target, etc.
>
>Trends change, things evolve and advance.  Nothing stays stagnant or it dies.
>
>I'm waiting for everything to go 100% mobile tied into the various 
>things.  Simple submission, filters for what you care about, Auto 
>date book, text sms, tied into desktop as well.  Things auto 
>updateing via WiFi or cell so that when you decide you want to go do 
>something, and based on what your filter criteria are, you can get 
>on your mobile device a list of club, event, underground, etc etc.
>
>Stuff like RSS is leading toward this in a big way, I'm just waiting 
>for some crazy uber geek to take all these unrelated emerging techs 
>to intergrate into the next system.
>
>However, I think lists will slowly wither, especially when you could 
>easily migrate to something like tribe, set up a private tribe, talk 
>as we do here about whatever, all nicely threaded, platform independent.
>Get everything here plus anything else you are into on a personal 
>level.  With Tribe you can also subscribe to a tribe via RSS so you 
>could watch your groups while using your fave email program at work 
>or what have you.
>
>ok...  now I'm just geek rambling.  ;)
>
>--S
>
>

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Tiesto sux...

This will be the only case I will ever defend Tiesto. For me, it's
about track selection. I don't care about how long and intricate the
mixes are. I've had some of my favorite tracks messed up by too much
interweaving, as a matter of fact. 20-45 seconds is plenty time to get
your point across and transition smoothly.

~Jenn~

From: Jennifer Clemente [mailto:jennifer.clemente@gmail.com] 
Sent: Monday, September 04, 2006 10:34 AM
To: Eric Spire

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Tiesto sux...

This will be the only case I will ever defend Tiesto. For me, it's
about track selection. I don't care about how long and intricate the
mixes are. I've had some of my favorite tracks messed up by too much
interweaving, as a matter of fact. 20-45 seconds is plenty time to get
your point across and transition smoothly.

~Jenn~

Personally I like to do as much research and asking around as possible
before trying any substance.

I found some to be fun and/or mind expanding with what I consider to be as
harmful as drinking or eating too much: bud, rolls, shrooms, lsd (very
occasionally)

On the other hand, I have had people tell me to just stay away from what
they considered to be the really bad shit: coke, H, crank, meth

I have still never tried those baddies to this day. No close minded jerk
here...

-Smithers

Subject: [sfraves] effects of ecstasy....

i thought i share this post from a different forum...it cracked me up...

adriana
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

          ecstasy has made my girlfriend look butt ugly in the dark :(    
                                                      
---------------------------------
                    hey guys, long time roller first time poster  i have rolled for a long time and have never had a bad experience off ecstasy. its a fantastic drug and has changed my life for the better. unfortunatly the same does not go for my girlfriend, she always spews (even if only one pill and sometimes half) and always feels sick at some stage regardless of how the rest of us have been hit.
 
 im assuming her body doesent agree with the drug or she is alot more sensitive to the chemicals but i dont let her do it very often becaues of that. but now comes the scary part, the other night we were rolling together at my house, we were havin a great time and one of my mates rang up to say he was coming around. we went out the front in the dark and sat on the road. i looked over at her and my heart stopped, I ACTUALLY SCREAMED LIKE A GIRL! i thought i was sitting next to a totally different person! her face was completly changed! in real life she is a model - she is extremly attractive! but fuck me dead she dead set looked like a cross between michael jackson, and one of them apes off planet of the apes. but her eyes were really dark and her lips were really dark and the rest of her skin was white as anything. HER HAIR EVEN LOOKED LIKE DUDES HAIR!! (but that could be cos it was tied back) either way i was scared, no matter how long or close or far away i looked at her
 she still looked the same - THIS WAS NO HALUCINATION! i took her to the light, as soon as she entered the light she was normal - same beutiful girl. i took her back to the dark, APEGIRL AFTER PLASTIC SURGERY WAS BACK! 
 
 i feel terrible i think i have hurt her with my reaction, i have to admit it would have been priceless to see though. what im here to ask thouhg is what could have possibly caused something like this!! i really just have no explanation at all, i cant imagine that being a halucination, theres no way it was! i've been trippin for 4 years and never seen anything like this! can someone please enlighten me? im confused as anything!


 		
---------------------------------
Yahoo! Messenger with Voice. Make PC-to-Phone Calls to the US (and 30+ countries) for 2/min or less.
--0-1178097699-1157484448=:17192--

------=_Part_30883_10521734.1157485528893
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=ISO-8859-1; format=flowed
Content-Transfer-Encoding: quoted-printable
Content-Disposition: inline

Shit that usually happens all the time with me, at around pill 3 or 4.  Thi=
s
one time some friends and i went to this warehouse party in the mission
somewhere (super small scale party, mellow but cool).  Anyway, we had these
pills called LifeSavers.  Big ass lookin pills, they had something else in
them because i've never hallucinated so badly off of just one pill.  At one
point during the party some thugs decided they wanted to try and bust in on
the party but the door guys held them off, so they decided to get some
fireworks and toss them in the mail slot.  They were going off all over and
they people throwing the party had the music shut off temporarily so we
could call the cops and get them removed from the area.  I remember at one
point i was sitting on the stairs talking to some people at the party and
they guy i was talking to started to morph right in front of me.  His face
turned inside out and flipped end over end and then turned normal again.
This happened a couple of times and then he asked me why i was laughing, so
i had to try and explain it to him.

That was all off the first pill, and i think that weekend we ended up doing
a 3 day/party binge and we got up to pill 9 by that Sunday.  Oh man, those
were the good ol days when i had braincells and cash to burn.

If you really wanna see your girlfriend get real ugly real quick, try

Hmm. I'd be speculating, however, that rarely stops me from typing.

Sometimes this particular substance lets you see into someone's heart rathe=
r than just noticing their outward appearance.

In the light her outward appearance was too strong for this effect to be no=
ticed, "in real life she is a model - she is extremly attractive! ", but in=
 the dark he could see what was underneath.

In other words, he probably just noticed that his girlfriend is a shallow b=
itch and his brain interpreted that realization as an "ugly" outward appear=
ance.

Just a theory of course since I don't know any of the people in question.

Sounds like someone put an RC in those pills. I once, a long time ago had A
LOT (1g) of 5-meo-mipt, which was active around the 5 mg range, well, I
accidentally took ~30mg cause my scale was off and I didn't know it (doesn'=
t
take much to make a scale go off in those ranges). I was sitting on the
couch and my friend was watching fox news, the Bill O'reilly show. That guy
turned into a devil, something I always felt about him. Seriously, horns
grew out of his head, his teeth turned to fangs, eyes blood red, and his
face grey hair like a caveman. The experience was so crazy that I quickly
got up to go to the bathroom. Blood was everywhere and when I pee'ed it was
all red (not really of course). Then I made the worst mistake, I stared at
myself in the mirror. My face went pale and wrinkles grew out, my facial an=
d
scalp hair grew long, then grey and then fell out, my eyes lost all life an=
d
then melted away to black holes where they once were. Then my skin started
flaking off and bugs covered over everything. All that was left was a skull=
.
I literally saw myself physically live the rest of my life. Then I closed m=
y
eyes, which was brighter then when they were open, and when I finally opene=
d
them everything was back to normal. Later that night I almost (thank god)
ended up in the ER due to my pulse rate going sky high and freaking out.
Moral of the story: clean your scale often and make sure it is balanced
properly.

The experience was so crazy that I later gave all my RCs to friends and
never again touched them.

Wow, poor soul. So what you are syaing is you love
listening to juke boxes that have an appearance you
appreciate, and jump around in a way that pleases you.
YAY.

I propose a new for of trance DJ just like the
broadway show "Avenue Q." It will be crowd
interactive. We can program a laptop to play the
tracks with 20 second overlaps, and people can put
their requests in before they get looped on E. Then,
as they are just coming on, a puppet acting as a bingo
master will pull the winning track selections from a
bingo wheel. Each tracklist will get its own puppet.
Then, as your tracklist comes on, you can lay on the
floor glowing in your self absorbed lustfullness, and
jump up when each breakdown comes, approximately every
2.5 minutes. Your puppet will also become very excited
at this moment, and propably pound a record into the
air for effect. After the break, the puppet will look
around for something to make him/her look busy for a
couple of more minutes, while you again laydown on the
floor. Repeat.

And of course, the puppets will all have special
shoes.

We will call the raves Muppet Y2K6.

Now I am going to vomit.

Eric

BT -  This Binary Universe.

Beats 2 channels and even the best winamp plugins (trust me I've tried them
all).

guitar loops that sometimes are chopped into just a milliseconds length.
Then out of nowhere comes the ephemeral pads bringing euphoria and
reflection in the best of ways.

Steve,

Regrets are pointless.   No regrets.

But do you think you could have achieved that any other way? You can change your perspective through sex, mediation, car racing, world travel, joining the peace corp., dancing, art, etc.  There are many possiblities.

It seems to me that drugs are a pretty dangerous path especially for certain people.  Other people seem to be able to dabble without wrecking their lives.  The problem is you don't know which one you are until its too late.

I'm certainly not a prude about it or anything, I grew up in Berkeley in the seventies, but I've also been close with people that have serious problems because of both legal and illegal drugs.

So I am wondering now, from where you are, do you think that you can you grow your perspective and explore new possibilities without drugs?  What is your path?

Just some late night thoughts, feel free to ignore if I'm in too deep.

Peace,

Peter

----- Original Message ----

POWER TO THE PEACEFUL FESTIVAL

THIS SATURDAY, 11-5

SPEEDWAY MEADOW IN GGP, SAN FRANCISCO


"Be Peace Now" is this year's theme reminding us that the path to a less violent world starts from within. Each one of us must commit to what we want to see reflected in the world. Or as Michael Franti sees it, "We can't change the world over night, but we can be a drop in the river that moves a mountain". 

In addition to the main stage of live music, PTTP also features morning yoga, an open-air art gallery, a healing arts tent, a DJ tent, vendors and food booths, eco village, kid's zone, bicycle coalition, and social, environmental & political organizations tabling & forums. A second stage has been added this year featuring an array of cutting edge local artists. Sunday September 10th at 1pm, Yoga Sangha of San Francisco will be hosting the Power to the Peaceful, "Be Peace Now Yoga Jam: A day of Yoga, Music and Activism", with Yoga teachers Shiva Rea, Nickie Doane and Eddie Modestini, Katchie Ananda, Acro-Yoga with Jason Nemer and Jenny Sauer-Klein, guest speakers Matthew and Terces Engelhart (Cafe Gratitude), Robi Damelin and Nadwa Sarandah and acoustic musical performances by Michael Franti, Jai Uttal others. 

PTTP Festival has been graced with inspirational performances by Michael Franti and Spearhead, KRS-One, String Cheese Incident, Saul Williams, Keller Williams, Blackalicious, Alice Walker, Ram Dass, Talib Kweli, Amy Goodman, The Coup, Digital Underground, Woody Harrelson, Lyrics Born, Anti-Flag, Jello Biafra and Angela Davis and many others.

DJ TENT:

Adnan
Garth
Maneesh the Twister
Hey Man!
Lioness

More Information:  http://www.powertothepeaceful.org/index.html

We have opted instead for an authoritarian system disguised as a Democracy. We pay through the nose for an enormous joke-of-a-government, let it push us around, and then wonder how all those assholes got in there." - Frank Zappa

Subject: RE: [sfraves] Minimal Tech/House mixes - suggestions?

Stuff on Kompakt Records is tight, so is Palette recordings, Viewlexx, 
Spectral, U-Freqs, Perlon and a buncha other labels I'm forgetting.

Some artists:

John Tejada
Arian Leviste
Isolee' (which is actually a bit more IDM)
L'usine (also a bit more IDM, but similar)
Justin Maxwell
Reinhard Voigt
Akufen
Carl Craig
Casey Hogan
Joel Mull

That oughtta get you started....

Subject: [sfraves] 30 years and a question

Content-Type: text/plain; charset=ISO-8859-1; format=flowed
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit
Content-Disposition: inline

Ok, I know I've had a lot of drama posts here lately, but I promise this
isn't one. I'm in a good mood, just want to hear what others do about these
type of thoughts.

I turned 30 a few months back, it seems a lot of time has passed. I have
lots of memories, good and bad that haunt me. They really really haunt me,
especially the good ones. I think back at when my child was a todler, or
times with friends and it's sad to have seen those times go. It's almost as
if it is over. For a long time I could just ignore memories and live in the
present and future, but lately it seems all I can do is drown myself in
these thoughts.

-- 
Steve Osteen is SlumberMachine
http://www.SlumberMachine.com

------=_Part_131949_15033587.1157588838835--

Subject: Re: [sfraves] 30 years and a question

I'm only 24, and for the most part I forget about all
those years that came before. But then I'll get in a
mood for thinking back, just sit in a nice comfortable
chair (or couch) and bring myself back.

For me it always seems I get this kind of churning,
but refreshing feeling in my gut, thinking about just
how technicolor things are when you were just a little
kid. I like my life now, but it would just be so much
fun to be that little 5 year old again, for just a
couple minutes. I can't even imagine what it's like
for ACTUAL old people (you know, you folks 30 and over
...)

Hmmm...Deep thoughts....
   
  Well, Im 28, on my way to 30 in a year and a half. (Gee, Im so excited.)
I also go through the same type of shit on a daily basis, and I guess the way I deal with it, is just remembering that 10 years from now, I can either:
   
  1)Dwell on it all over and over again, with the same result occuring each time
  or
  2)Realize that if I stay in that frame of mind, Ill be doing the same thing 10 years from now and feeling even worse, because then Id be even older, with less time remaining in my life to create new memories.
   
  Sometimes, its a great release to spin, play an instrument (not the skin flute!) or even just write your thoughts down...
   
  My 2-
   
  P.S.-- I was on this list like 6-7 years ago, moved to AZ where the "scene" was so retarded I stopped going to parties.
  Anyway, I just recently moved backto the south bay, and im interested in seeing what its like out here these days.
  Wheres all the dope househeads at?!?!?!
   
  I used to hella dig jeno, garth, erik brown, spun, etc
  My tastes are mostly deep house, downtempo, funk, disco, etc..
   
  Can anyone give me some recommendations on local djs, the vibe of parties these days, etc??
   
  Thanks for reading,
   
  Its great to back!

At 06:50 PM 9/6/2006, Sarilion wrote:
>I went to a benefit for Erik Brown a couple years back (at least?), so I'm not sure he's still spinning..

>sarilion

I have much respect for Erik.  Yes, he is still spinning (house of course) and is one of the Yerba Bueno Discos artists:


SOUTH HAMPTON 
 
Erik Brown, also known as South Hampton, began his music career as a singer and drummer in a high school rock band. However, with the explosion of the Bay Area rave scene, it was only natural that he move away from his rock roots into DJ work. He quickly became a fixture in the Bay Area party scene, producing and spinning records at the Temple, Magic, and Bodyrock events. 

Erik quickly developed a well-deserved reputation as one of the North Bays most notorious party monsters. He produced the best events, played the best music, and partied harder than any one else in the scene. Unfortunately, the party was brought to an untimely end with the death of San Francisco's underground rave scene, paired with an accident which left Erik paralyzed from the waist down. After a year or two of soul-searching and recovery, Erik threw himself back into the arms of the house music he loved, becoming serious about music production and even opening a very ahead-of-its-time record and clothing store in his native Santa Rosa. 

For 2004 and early 2005, Erik left his old persona behind, changing his name to South Hampton. He joined forces with Yerba Buena Discos, putting his funky stamp on both the music and the artistic style of the label. It was a natural fit - disco plus funk. However, after producing some great tracks, Erik has left us to launch his own label, Box Ready Records. 

As for his contributions to the underground house music scene, an unusually reflective Erik comments on his continued success, "You can continue enjoying your dreams in the wake of adversity."


http://www.yerbabuenadiscos.com/artists.html





http://www.asambleapopulardeoaxaca.com/ 

MySpace:  http://www.myspace.com/DJApollo 

Tribenet:   <http://people.tribe.net/djapollo2k>http://people.tribe.net/djapollo2k 
                
House Music 101:  http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm

"Americans like to talk about (or be told about) Democracy but, when put to the test, usually find it to be an 'inconvenience.' We have opted instead for an authoritarian system disguised as a Democracy. We pay through the nose for an enormous joke-of-a-government, let it push us around, and then wonder how all those assholes got in there." - Frank Zappa 

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of the rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will gradually become visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

Subject: Re: [sfraves] 30 years and a question

I'm going to be 45 next week.  

But I see the world with fresh eyes everyday.  It helps that I have a 1.5 and 3 year old running around to remind me that the smallest most trival thing can be amazing.

There are two parts to being old.  One part is in your body.  Stuff wears out.  You creak and crack.  You can exercise, eat right, etc.  but in the end there isn't much you can do about this part.

The other part is in your mind.  Most of the people I know that are my age act old.  They think old.  They become old, because of their thinking not their bodies.  This part you can do something about.  You don't ever need to be old in your mind.

Get a pail and shovel, head to the beach, and build a sand castle. Roll down a grassy hill.  Get some fingerpaints. 

Don't be a grown up!

Peace,

Peter

----- Original Message ----
From: Justin Johnson <justinsuperstar@yahoo.com>
To: sfraves@hyperreal.org
Sent: Wednesday, September 6, 2006 5:58:31 PM
Subject: Re: [sfraves] 30 years and a question

I'm only 24, and for the most part I forget about all
those years that came before. But then I'll get in a
mood for thinking back, just sit in a nice comfortable
chair (or couch) and bring myself back.

For me it always seems I get this kind of churning,
but refreshing feeling in my gut, thinking about just
how technicolor things are when you were just a little
kid. I like my life now, but it would just be so much
fun to be that little 5 year old again, for just a
couple minutes. I can't even imagine what it's like
for ACTUAL old people (you know, you folks 30 and over
...)

>isn't one. I'm in a good mood, just want to hear what others do about these
>type of thoughts.
>
>I turned 30 a few months back, it seems a lot of time has passed. I have
>lots of memories, good and bad that haunt me. They really really haunt me,
>especially the good ones. I think back at when my child was a todler, or
>times with friends and it's sad to have seen those times go. It's almost as
>if it is over. For a long time I could just ignore memories and live in the
>present and future, but lately it seems all I can do is drown myself in
>these thoughts.
>

I will be turning 30 myself in January and yes, those mid-20 memories are
truly missed. I treasure those memories, use them to help me grow and
realize the world around me.

I cannot let regret set in, it will just ruin them for me. To me those
memories should always give me happiness and not pain and sorrow. Yes you
cannot relive those happy times but if you could, they would not be as
valued as they are to you now.

There are more happy memories to come Steve. Just keep that chin up and
consider yourself fortunate you had such wonderful times to begin
with...most people dont/cant/wont.

-Smithers

At 11:04 AM 9/7/2006, Steve Osteen wrote:
>Sorry, the question was: how do you deal with memories?.
>

The "times" have not left you Steve.  In Buddhist-Hindu-Taoist and other traditions, now reinforced by modern physics, time is not linear but cyclical, repeating in a loop like a Mbius strip and always returning to the source.  The concept of linear time in the West is rather recent and arose with the use of mechanical watches and other devices.  Consensus reality is not "truth," merely a convenient construct -- an ilusion.  I think there is no past, present or future:)  Your "memories" are as "real" as the cubical you inhabit right now.  Not to worry.

Apollo

At 01:45 PM 9/7/2006, dangrsmind@yahoo.com wrote:
>When did Temple open?  I haven't even heard about it...
>
>It will be interesting to be in there again.

Prolly be a good idea, then, to buy the yearly $200.00 "Bliss Pass" and save on clubbing essentials like bottle service and expedited drink service.  The Temple opens this Saturday with Jeno and Galen in the "Catacombs."

Ain't the old DV8, Peter, so don't expect that original psychedelic vibe:)  Keith Haring Room is gone, of course, and the interior is much more upscale -- renovated extensively.  Not for the Pete Avila-type crowd.  But wait, that crowd is well over 30 now so maybe.  Lotta bottles instead of wee pills.

My two favorite clubs in the late 80's were the DV8 and 1015.  I can always revisit in my memories.  Dance all nite long in the fog.

Subject: Re: [sfraves] 30 years and a question

Everybody told me that turning 30 was gonna be major insane oh no suxxor shit.  I heard that from many many people.  I had personally been going through serious age issues since 25- I got started early, so it didn't hit me like the proverbial ton of bricks initially.

Since then I've been going through serious old-raver-and-music-days withdrawl off and on.  Some serious rose-colored glasses shit.  My 20s were all about getting nothing done and dating girls who mistreated me, interspersed with some pretty amazing moments.  My late 20s and early 30s have been a fricking awesome breeze in comparison, if you look with an unjaundiced eye at it.

I think my 30s are going to continue to only get better.  The rave scene I loved is dead, or perhaps what lived inside of me in those days is dead, but my spirit lives on and has fun in new avenues now.  I'm living with an amazing girl and making the best music I've ever made.  I think it's gonna be alright.

I think I'm more put upon by the state of our country than I ever was by age worries.  Now THAT's some life-sucking shit.

Keep on keepin' on and most of all know you can always lose yourself in music when you feel down.

-g


----- Original Message ----
From: Ryan Smith <sf_smith@comcast.net>
To: The Love Underground <sfraves@hyperreal.org>
Sent: Thursday, September 7, 2006 11:13:11 AM
Subject: RE: [sfraves] 30 years and a question

I will be turning 30 myself in January and yes, those mid-20 memories are
truly missed. I treasure those memories, use them to help me grow and
realize the world around me.

I cannot let regret set in, it will just ruin them for me. To me those
memories should always give me happiness and not pain and sorrow. Yes you
cannot relive those happy times but if you could, they would not be as
valued as they are to you now.

There are more happy memories to come Steve. Just keep that chin up and
consider yourself fortunate you had such wonderful times to begin
with...most people dont/cant/wont.

-Smithers

Subject: Re: [sfraves] 30 years and a question

I was identifying with a client today that was 50+ with two grown 
children, talking about how turbulent her life has been.  She's a 
little stressed, but mostly happy now that she's found a good job 
with benefits. It doesn't sound like there's any rest in our futures; 
we both agreed we'd probably work until we die.

I'll be thirty in just two years, but I too have been thinking about 
it since I was 25, so I wouldn't be crushed by it all at once.  I've 
been setting goals for personal growth over long periods of time.  I 
think it's only going to get better, and while I cherish the memories 
I have, I don't wish to live in the past.

I think the only time when I was truly happy, was when I was a little 
kid, and every need was taken care of.  Ignorance is bliss, but it's 
possible to be happy w/o being blissful.


sarilion

From: Deepfog <sfgroove@deepfog.com>
Date: Thu, 7 Sep 2006 22:57:28 -0400
To: The Twilight Laser Outpost (West) <sfraves@hyperreal.org>
X-Mailer: Apple Mail (2.752.2)
X-Spam-Rating: taz3.hyperreal.org 1.6.2 0/1000/N
Subject: Re: [sfraves] 30 years and a question

i think each decade brings with it new experiences and we're lucky  
only to hold on to some of the memories of the good times of our  
younger years; for me, some of those people are dead, or we've moved  
on and lost contact.  i try not to focus on the bad things that have  
happened; i believe they're a good reference point for lessons  
learned, but too much attracts more bad things.

i remember someone i once looked up to at 40 mentioned his life was  
half over.  and though i learned a lot from that person, i want  
more.  i'm planning to live to 150.  that's fine, call me crazy, the  
typical reactions i get are either you're crazy or i don't want to  
live that long.  it would be my strong hope that some of the people i  
know or have known in the past and today would be there too.

anyway, the reason i'm bringing this up is that goal gives me  
something to live for, and the curiosity of what is to come is  
exciting to me.  it can be exciting to any of you, too, that allow  
it, and i think you might find if you allow that to flow into your  
being, you might find it can put a very fresh outlook on those past  
memories you were, oh so lucky to experience, even the bad things.

and aren't we lucky to even remember them?  according to science, we  
cast of millions of dead cells every day and grow new ones.   
physically, we're a whole new person every, how long?  i don't think  
you need to have a goal to live a really long life to be happy, but i  
do think curiosity is a cornerstone to keeping the mind and body  
vibrant and healthy.


-d

Subject: Re: [sfraves] 30 years and a question

You have to be careful about thinking your life is "half over" I think.

I am reminded of an incident I heard about where the Buddhist teacher Pema Chodron was saying goodbye to some students after a teaching.  One of the students said "See you next time!" to which Pema responded "Unless we die!"

Today might be your last day.  You might think you life is half over and it might really be 99% over.  You might never get that new mixer you are saving up for.  You might never see your wife ro girlfriend or child again.

Or perhaps there will be some medical miracle and your life will really be only 10% over.  You just don't know.   

Live each day like its your last.  Live each day like its your first.  Easy to say and hard to do.

Regards,

Peter

Subject: [sfraves] Saturday: Burlesque Show

Hope to see you all at our show! We have some new and old peices for
your viewing enjoyment! Come early for the burlesque and stay for the
readings!

Saturday September 9th...


Raina Bird presents:

Sex, Drugs, and Rock-n-Roll
A Night of Tits & Lit

Burlesque dancers and the best authors of transgressive literature
come together for a night of Sex, Drugs, and Rock-n-Roll.

September 9, 2006
Shotwell Studios  3252A 19th Street @ Shotwell
San Francisco
Doors 9:45PM Show 10:15PM
$3 - $5


FEATURE PERFORMERS:

Raina Bird, Tina Butcher, Tony DuShane, Lilycat, Carmelo Valone
& the Solid Golddiggers Burlesque Dancers

For more information contact: rainabird@hotmail.com
415-847-4026

BIOS:


Raina Bird was born in a cult run by a fat bald guy with 9 wives who
said he was the living incarnation of the divine. She now hates
hippies and religion with equal fervor. She is currently writing a
memoir about the experience. Her work has appeared in Morbid
Curiosity, Instant City and cherrybleeds. She is heavily tattooed,
very fond of her pet rat and leaves her house as little as possible

Tina Butcher - AKA Madison Young is a San Francisco based writer,
artist, and international bondage model. Tina's writing has been
published in such magazines as Girlfriends, On Our Backs, Bitch,
Herbivore, Skin Two, and in the anthology "Baby Remember My Name."
edited by Michelle Tea. Currently writes travel articles for Velvet
Park, and reviews for Skin Two, and is completing her memoir entitled
The Tail of a Bondage Model; Memoirs of Madison Young". Madison Young
has traveled the world working with some of the best bondage and
fetish photographers and rope artists in the business. Madison has
been published in over 100 web sites, numerous magazines including
Hustler's Taboo and Leg World, and score of bondage and fetish videos,
international bondage performances, and has started her own line of
bondage videos and websites including www.madisonBond.com and
www.Tied4Sex.com.

Tony DuShane- spends all his time writing, working on his radio show
Drinks with Tony, editing the literary 'zine Cherry Bleeds and bench
pressing women who weigh 165 or less.
His shoe size is 10 and his liver is strong.

Lilycat  Is a strong believer of supporting underground artists, loves
to write, is a fan of sex and rock-n-roll, knows a lot of people on
drugs, and likes to talk. You can find out about her at lilycat.com

Carmelo Valone- the troubled Carmelo Valone grew up surrounded by old
money and living dead residents of the suburbs of Connecticut. In the
early and dysfunctional 1990s he suffered a =8Cbreakdown=B9 and spent a
number of seasons in and out of McLean=B9s Psychiatric hospital. The
former home to numerous other troubled writers such as Silvia Plath,
Anne Sexton, and Susana Kaysen. He is a writer and is currently
working on a darkly humorous memoir about his young adult life in the
hospital called; "The Sex Life of a Lunatic" a search for love within
lunacy. He also has several screenplays and has acted and makes weird
electronic music. He loves to watch Prison Break and feeds ducks at
the Hollywood Forever cemetery.

BURLESQUE PERFORMANCES BY:

Solid Goldiggers Burlesque
A San Francisco based group founded in 2004 as a ladies night escape
from significant others. Consists of dancers Danielle Sipple Katie
Rose, Charlie Fisher, Bene, Melinda, and JoJo who all come from
various dance and theater backgrounds. Fusing the various dance styles
of ballet, theater, funk, and hip hop with traditional burlesque. The
Solid Goldiggers bring you performances like you've never seen that
accentuate all that is dance performance art with a twist of vintage
style and glamour.

Performing at various venues, such as Lingba Lounge, Element, Nickies,
Fashion events, and private events over the past year and a half.
Solid Goldiggers Burlesque continues to bring an element of excitement
and class to the world of dance entertainment while empowering
themselves, each other and their Audiences.

Subject: Re: [sfraves] 30 years and a question

In college I read Suzuki's Zen Mind, Beginer's Mind as well as Tarthang Tulku's Gesture of Balance.  I can recommend both of these books without hesitation and I think they are both highly accesible. Also find a copy of Zen Flesh,Zen Bones, which is one of my favorite books of all time.  I mentioned Pema Chodron, and I think you might find her books The Places that Scare You: A Guide to Fearlessness in Difficult Times and Comfortable with Uncertainty: 108 Teachings on Cultivating Fearlessness and Compassion useful.  Her writing style is direct, simple, and almost touching I think.  Chodron was a student of the infamous Chogyam Trungpa, and many of his books are fantastic.  I especially like The Lion's Roar: An Introduction to Tantra, Crazy Wisdom, and Training the Mind and Cultivating Loving Kindness but his books The Myth of Freedom and the Way of Meditation and Cutting Through Spiritual Materialism are also important.  Interestingly I haven't found any of the Dalai Lama's
 books to be that compelling, but I know a lot of other people like them.  I'd be delighted to share any of the books in my library with you.

Lao Tzu's Tao Te Ching is a must read also.  Maybe some else can recommend a specific translation.

Depending on what appeals to you there are lots of other books out there.  FWIW I am a practicing Tibetan Buddhist, but this style doesn't appeal to a lot of people.  Most people I know prefer the sedate minimalist approach of Zen, as compared to the more "psychedelic" Tibetan schools.  Check out the Tibetan Mahamudra and Dzogchen teachings in particular.

I've practiced in the highly controversial New Kadampa Tradition which is headed by Geshe Kelsang Gyatso.  I find Geshe-la's books to be accessible and practical, if often a bit dry and boring.  I'd recommend the new version of the Meditation Handbook as well as Clear Light of Bliss.  You should know however that NKT is at odds with the traditional Buddhist schools and Tibetan government as headed by the Dalai Lama.  In fact the Dalai Lama has banned one of the primary NKT practices, which FWIW, I don't practice either.  This gets a bit obscure to say the least, I can provide links if you are interested.

One thing I think is important as a westerner is addressing the entire reincarnation thing.  To put it bluntly I've found it hard/mpossible to buy into the traditional teachings on reincarnation or the Tibetan system of reincarnate teachers and lamas.  I've found the Dzogchen teachings to be much more in line with a modern scientific thinking here.  A good resource online for Tibetan Buddhism in general is the Berzin Archives: http://www.berzinarchives.com/

Finally, I've recently gotten interested in Shaivism which predates Buddhist and Hindu tantric practices.  I read some books by Daniel Odier which were nice, and I can recommed his book on the "sacred tremor" or Spandakarika in particular.  I've been reading Osho's (aka Rajaneesh) Book of Secrets which is a commentary on the Hindu VIGYANA BHAIRAVA TANTRA which is also included as an appendix in Zen Flesh, Zen Bones.  Osho has fallen into disrepute because of the actions of his followers up in Oregon, but I've found this book to be trully amazing and insightful.  And its available online in totality for free: http://www.oshoworld.com/tantra_medi/index.asp

I'm actually looking for a new Sangha (spiritual community) so if you are ever interested, I'd be willing to go with you to any meditaton center or class.  I know it was a bit weird for me at first and I went alone.  The worst part was the music, which in NKT isn't traditional Tibetan music which I would have prefered, but rather sort of bad folk music versions of TIbetan chants. Anyway we are lucky in San Francisco to have a great wealth of choices in this area.

Peace,

Peter

> i think each decade brings with it new experiences and we're lucky

> younger years; for me, some of those people are dead, or we've moved
> on and lost contact.  i try not to focus on the bad things that have
> happened; i believe they're a good reference point for lessons
> learned, but too much attracts more bad things.
>

> half over.  and though i learned a lot from that person, i want
> more.  i'm planning to live to 150.  that's fine, call me crazy, the
> typical reactions i get are either you're crazy or i don't want to
> live that long.  it would be my strong hope that some of the people i
> know or have known in the past and today would be there too.
>
> anyway, the reason i'm bringing this up is that goal gives me
> something to live for, and the curiosity of what is to come is
> exciting to me.  it can be exciting to any of you, too, that allow
> it, and i think you might find if you allow that to flow into your
> being, you might find it can put a very fresh outlook on those past
> memories you were, oh so lucky to experience, even the bad things.
>
> and aren't we lucky to even remember them?  according to science, we
> cast of millions of dead cells every day and grow new ones.
> physically, we're a whole new person every, how long?  i don't think
> you need to have a goal to live a really long life to be happy, but i
> do think curiosity is a cornerstone to keeping the mind and body

Ben,
   
  How's it going man? Ticket was for speeding Northbound on 280. When the CHP officer pulled me over, he said I was "paced by an aircraft doing 90 mph," although he had not witnessed this act himself. The irony is that I had my cruise control set around 70 to safely keep up with the flow of traffic.
   
  I was advised by SFR members to submit a plea of not guilty by mail along with my "bail" ($185.00). Also, a couple SFR heads recommended TicketAssassin which offers shareware & templates to people like me that need help in these jams. It cost $25 bucks for the membership, however it's money well spent IMHO.
   
  The court mailed me some documents pertaining to a "Trial by Written Declaration," in which I could submit a statement & evidence. Using a template from Ticket Assassin as the backbone of my written testimony, I managed to deliver a compelling case which was dismissed yesterday (yup, it took them a full month to review my testimony, even though the "trial" date was Aug. 8th). Found all this out over the phone today when I called them to check the status of my case. I guess it takes them six (6) weeks to mail my money back, but that still beats another kick in the nuts. 
   
  Best,
   
  Chuck

  CC: SFRaves

Subject: Re: [sfraves] 30 years and a question

 >be here now

i am probably the only one that can't stand this phrase but it's  
because the only time i ever hear it is when some guy is trying to  
get in my pants and he's like fending off my anticipation of future  
regret.

but about past memories.
have you ever gone back to visit a house you lived in, far back in  
your past? Say when you were 6.
in your mind you remember the tree in the backyard being gigantic.   
the corner lot with the thick trees was a forest.  and then when you  
go back it looks so different, so much smaller.  the tree isn't  
really that big and your forest was really just some scrub brush.   
even the loompia at the local filipino restaurant doesn't taste the  
same as your young childhood memories remember the sweet plum sauce  
just was more sweeter like liquid candy.  and you were so sure of  
things and spoke with conviction on how you felt, unvarnished.

it would be nice to feel that way again.

i don't know how other people manage to renew themselves, or feel  
that liberation that comes with innocence.  sometimes people buy  
stuff, toys for grown ups, hoping that it will satisfy.  others have  
children of their own so they can experience that newness again.  i  
mean i see what you're saying.

  people talk about the movie "groove" and i wonder is it really like  
that? (why am i here)  and if i have a good time at one place, like  
one good night, can it ever be repeated?  the euphoria is so intense  
there's a fear that no, it won't happen again and i will be  
disappointed.  and it's this fear of disappointment that separates  
this from children, who lack that cynicism and doubt.

i've been painting a lot lately, and they are childhood memories.   
impressions.  just the colors, and movement are the focus.  i  
remember so well the tastes, the smells, the magenta flowers, the  
blue green Gulf, blinding white sand, a calf sized tattoo of the  
Battle of Coral Sea and Doolittle's Raid, horn rimmed glasses, cigar  
smoke, aquamarine shag carpet, fire ants, inch worms, riding horses  
through a flooded field like the mt dew commercial, scorpions,  
mesquite trees, granite rock jettis

what are some of your memories?

deni

>> i think each decade brings with it new experiences and we're lucky
>> only to hold on to some of the memories of the good times of our
>> younger years; for me, some of those people are dead, or we've moved
>> on and lost contact.  i try not to focus on the bad things that have
>> happened; i believe they're a good reference point for lessons
>> learned, but too much attracts more bad things.
>>
>> i remember someone i once looked up to at 40 mentioned his life was
>> half over.  and though i learned a lot from that person, i want
>> more.  i'm planning to live to 150.  that's fine, call me crazy, the
>> typical reactions i get are either you're crazy or i don't want to
>> live that long.  it would be my strong hope that some of the people i
>> know or have known in the past and today would be there too.
>>
>> anyway, the reason i'm bringing this up is that goal gives me
>> something to live for, and the curiosity of what is to come is
>> exciting to me.  it can be exciting to any of you, too, that allow
>> it, and i think you might find if you allow that to flow into your
>> being, you might find it can put a very fresh outlook on those past
>> memories you were, oh so lucky to experience, even the bad things.
>>
>> and aren't we lucky to even remember them?  according to science, we
>> cast of millions of dead cells every day and grow new ones.
>> physically, we're a whole new person every, how long?  i don't think
>> you need to have a goal to live a really long life to be happy, but i
>> do think curiosity is a cornerstone to keeping the mind and body
>> vibrant and healthy.

i am probably the only one that can't stand this phrase but it's

but about past memories.
have you ever gone back to visit a house you lived in, far back in  
your past? Say when you were 6.
in your mind you remember the tree in the backyard being gigantic.   
the corner lot with the thick trees was a forest.  and then when you  
go back it looks so different, so much smaller.  the tree isn't  
really that big and your forest was really just some scrub brush.

>> it might really be 99% over.  You might never get that new mixer  
>> you are
>> saving up for.  You might never see your wife ro girlfriend or  
>> child again.
>>
>> Or perhaps there will be some medical miracle and your life will  
>> really be
>> only 10% over.  You just don't know.
>>
>> Live each day like its your last.  Live each day like its your
>> first.  Easy to say and hard to do.
>>
>> Regards,
>>
>> Peter
>>
>>
>>
>> ----- Original Message ----
>> From: Deepfog <sfgroove@deepfog.com>
>> To: The Twilight Laser Outpost <sfraves@hyperreal.org>
>> Sent: Thursday, September 7, 2006 7:57:28 PM
>> Subject: Re: [sfraves] 30 years and a question
>>
>> i think each decade brings with it new experiences and we're lucky
>> only to hold on to some of the memories of the good times of our
>> younger years; for me, some of those people are dead, or we've moved
>> on and lost contact.  i try not to focus on the bad things that have
>> happened; i believe they're a good reference point for lessons
>> learned, but too much attracts more bad things.
>>
>> i remember someone i once looked up to at 40 mentioned his life was
>> half over.  and though i learned a lot from that person, i want
>> more.  i'm planning to live to 150.  that's fine, call me crazy, the
>> typical reactions i get are either you're crazy or i don't want to
>> live that long.  it would be my strong hope that some of the people i
>> know or have known in the past and today would be there too.
>>
>> anyway, the reason i'm bringing this up is that goal gives me
>> something to live for, and the curiosity of what is to come is
>> exciting to me.  it can be exciting to any of you, too, that allow
>> it, and i think you might find if you allow that to flow into your
>> being, you might find it can put a very fresh outlook on those past
>> memories you were, oh so lucky to experience, even the bad things.
>>
>> and aren't we lucky to even remember them?  according to science, we
>> cast of millions of dead cells every day and grow new ones.
>> physically, we're a whole new person every, how long?  i don't think
>> you need to have a goal to live a really long life to be happy, but i
>> do think curiosity is a cornerstone to keeping the mind and body
>> vibrant and healthy.
>>
>>
>> -d

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Incredible light-emitting shirts

Those are amazing. Philips put together a book called Visions of the Future (http://www.design.philips.com/about/design/section-13482/index.html) back in 1995, and many of the ideas put forward there are coming into being today.

I'm generally pretty skeptical of consumer electronics company's visions for our future, but at least Philip's vision recognizes the place of human emotion and feeling, as well as celebrating innovative industrial design.

Peace,

Peter

Saturday September 9th...


Raina Bird presents:

Sex, Drugs, and Rock-n-Roll
A Night of Tits & Lit

Burlesque dancers and the best authors of transgressive literature
come together for a night of Sex, Drugs, and Rock-n-Roll.

September 9, 2006
Shotwell Studios  3252A 19th Street @ Shotwell
San Francisco
Doors 9:45PM Show 10:15PM
$3 - $5

Raina Bird, Tina Butcher, Tony DuShane, Lilycat, Carmelo Valone
& the Solid Golddiggers Burlesque Dancers

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Re: get freaky?

I wasn't there but I'm guessing that it follows a certain pattern that
Get Freaky parties have gone for a while.  I may be speaking out of my
ass but I've talked to lots of friends that just won't go to their
parties cause their got tired of it.  The sound doesn't change much,
Lorin and Bassnectar always play, the talent isn't normally as
talented as they should be and there isn't much room made for anyone
new.

This party seem to show a much more diverse array of music than I've
seen them do in a while.  I was hoping that they might be changing
things but it sounds like it hasn't.

And a big segment burner crowd in the bay seems to have a habit with
the Get Freaky parties.  Old habits die hard.  They have been going
for so long now, how can they tell if it's bad.  Not to mention the
bar is not set that high on the playa so this may translate to putting
up with bad djs in the club.

My two cents.  Take it or leave it.

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Re: get freaky?

generally when bassnectar plays he draws a huge crowd
to the dancefloor. it's hot , sweaty, debaucherous....
quite a lovely dancefloor really, cept i can't get
into his music. soon as he's done playing the
dancefloor, and often the party itself, clear. in my
time here in sf promoting i've come across the
attitude many times that if basssnectar isn't playing,
it isn't worth going to. regardless of who else is on
the bill, if he's on it the focus is on him. i respect
the fact that he has such a devoted following, more
power to him. but frankly, i hate their attitude and
am always diappointed to see bassnectar on a line-up
and hope he never plays a party that i invest any
energy into, as i feel it would be wasted.

Hey there,

It's the official pre-playa t'rowdown, everyone! This one's gonna be hot hot
HOT, with Aaron Jae and Donna Matrix joining myself and Marc(O) on the
decks. The energy is insanely high around our bay and our community right
now, with less than a week until the big one gets underway. We're all busy
getting everything together, yes, but you KNOW you need to get out and see
everyone, hear some choice, premium, grade-A beats, burn off some of that
steam, shake your ass and embrace the energy. Milk it, y'all! It's the
official playa-vibe Crooked!


Crooked
Wednesday, 8/23
Nickie's BBQ, 460 Haight St. @ Fillmore, SF

Subject: [sfraves] BSP: DIRTY w/ Chris Carter - Thurs, Sept 14 @ Mighty

DIRTY
Thursday, September 14th
Mighty (119 Utah st)
10pm-230am
21+ w/ID
$5 b4 11pm & $7 after

It's time for another rendition of Dirty, and this time Evil Breaks is
bringing back one of our favorite producers of all time to help us as
we try and raise some money for our Love Fest float. Besides the good
cause, this lineup is completely wicked, with a price and venue that
you just can't beat. This will also be one of Chris's last tours for a
while as his work visa is about to expire. 2 rooms of nasty is what
you can expect, with a great vibe and even better music.

Featuring:

Chris Carter (TCR/Rec. Records/Botchit & Scarper/Forged) - London, UK

Chris has established himself as a popular DJ and has toured all over
Europe as well as the USA, Asia and Australia. His mixes have been
aired on radio stations such as Radio1, Kiss, Ministry, Groovetech and
stations across Europe and the US.

Since starting to release his own productions in 1997, he has had a
steady stream of releases on a number UK based breaks labels including
TCR, Botchit + Scarper, Forged, En:Vision, Secret Agent, Track,and his
own Record Records amongst others, earning him a reputation as a
master of well-crafted left-of-centre dancefloor tunes.

His remix work includes tracks for Forged, Botchit, Cup of Chi,
En:Vision, Passenger,and most recently as Roxiller on Sober,
Functional and Broke Records.


the Evil Breakers for the night:

Aaron Jae (Evil Breaks/XM Radio/AaronJae.com)
Bam (Evil Breaks/Invibe.com)
M.O.D. (Evil Breaks)


Super Duper guest dj's:

Syd Gris (Opel Productions/Opulent Temple)
Jeffrey Allen (LOST/Bambuddha Lounge/Proton Radio)
Jared (Deep End/In Deep)
Evinrude (Renegade Ferrets/Crooked)

this and all of our events.....

In 5, 4, 3, 2, 1...Blastoff! 

Mark your calendars (Saturday, October 14th from 10 PM to 5 AM) for the underground party of the fall in San Francisco. A fantastic space, great people, a dancefloor that will not stop, an incredible soundsystem, and sounds that will transform you into a supercharged mass of kinetic energy all night long! 

We have Chicago House Legend Roy Davis Jr of Large Records and Ubiquity Records, local sensation JT Donaldson of Om Records and Gallery Music, Homero Espinosa, Eric Sharp, and Ryan D. housing it up in the Soul Stompers room. Breaking it down in the Bass Invaders room will be Space Cowboys' dancefloor demolitionist Mancub along with Lachlan, Native Intelligence, and Mycho Cocoa. 

Call 415-412-0406 the night of for details. You'll be glad you did. :) 

See you on the dancefloor! 

The Rock It Science Crew 
 Eric Sharp

Subject: [sfraves] bsp: Sat.Sept.16 [KONTROL] w/ Alex Smoke LIVE (Soma:Glasgow) + Justin Martin!

Saturday, September 16

[ K O N T R O L ]

minimal techno + avant house
every 3rd Saturday at Rx Gallery


featuring from Glasgow, Scotland:

===>  ALEX SMOKE - live!  <===

( Soma . Vakant . Crosstown Rebels . Trapez . Ware )

Hot off a headlining performance at Seattle's Decibel Festival,
Alex Smoke brings his achingly lush, musical, and emotive
techno to San Francisco for the first time ever. Hear for yourself
why the young lad from Glasgow has become and international
sensation in just two short years.


plus special guest:

===>  JUSTIN MARTIN  <===

( Dirtybird . Classic . Buzzin' Fly . Om )

One year after his unforgettable performance opening for Isolee,
San Francisco's brightest young producer and DJ returns with
what's sure to be another jaw-dropping set crafted especailly
for KONTROL.


with resident DJs:

ALLAND BYALLO  ( liebe*detail . kvadrat produkt . mo's ferry )

9pm-2am / 21+ / $10

limited capacity, arrive early to assure entry!

______________________________________________


Biography: ALEX SMOKE

Alex Smoke is unique talent to emerge from the Glasgow music scene.
This young producer is pushing the boundaries of electronic music with
his innovative fusion of deep European minimalism with emotional
strings and intellegent electro rhythms. Alex has a classical music
background which reveals itself in the quality of his arrangements. In
the past two years the music world has witnessed his rapid ascent
through the ranks of the techno elite. Since the 2005 release of his
brilliant debut LP on Soma, 'Incommunicado' he has been booked to play
the clubs and festivals of the UK, Europe and beyond. His coveted
releases on Berlin label Vakant have cemented his club credentials and
found their way into boxes and laptops of innovative DJs everywhere.
Not content with a slew of killer twelves, Alex Smoke remixes have
constantly been in demand, recently renovating Mylo, Alex Under and
Vector Lovers. 2006 has shaped up to be another monumental one for
Alex Smoke with the release of his second LP, 'Paradolia' and
subsequent UK, European, and US live tours.

website:
http://www.somarecords.com/artists/alexsmoke/

discography:
http://www.discogs.com/artist/Alex%20Smoke

Alex Smoke - Don't See The Point (mp3 sample):
http://mp3.juno.co.uk/MP3/SF198216-01-01-02.mp3

Alex Smoke - Meany (mp3 sample):
http://mp3.juno.co.uk/MP3/SF210583-01-01-01.mp3

___________________________________________

Biography: JUSTIN MARTIN

Justin Martin is one of the few house DJs that successfully bridges
the gap between being commercially successful and staying true to the
underground. His sound has been described as both melodic and tough,
with releases ranging from the dynamic "Cicada" on dirtybird to the
slamming "Magnificent" remix for Iz and Diz on OM records.  Justin
first gained international acclaim for his single, "The Sad Piano," on
Ben Watt's Buzzin'fly label. The single made its way into many A-List
DJ crates as well as receiving many accolades from critics. Over time,
Justin developed a more edgy sound in his hometown of San Francisco.
He helped develop the local dirtybird label with his good friend,
Claude VonStroke, releasing several amazing singles and remixes.
Justin considers himself lucky to be making music and is always a
humble, but rocking presence on the dance floor. Stay tuned for some
amazing collaborations with his brother Christian coming soon on
dirtybird as well as a mix compilation on the Om Winter Sessions
Series.

website:
http://www.dirtybirdrecords.com/justin_martin.html

discography:
http://www.discogs.com/artist/Justin%20Martin

promo dj mix (feb 2006):
http://www.dirtybirdrecords.com/audio/mixes/take_me_out.mp3


__________________________________________


Coming next month:

AKUFEN ( Musique Risque . Perlon . Mutek_Rec // Montreal )


http://www.kontrolsf.com

Hey all,

Just wanted to drop a note, say hello, and introduce myself. I'm in  
the process of moving back to California and into San Fran  
specifically. I'm from the general area but have never lived in the  
city before and I have been living out of the state and/or country  
for the last 5 years or so. Currently stuck in the mountains a couple  
hours away until I find a job in the city but I'll be making frequent  
trips down there for that purpose. Was down last weekend looking for  
something to do and realized the limitations imposed by my lack of  
contacts (friends) in the city. Was quite active in the scene in S.  
Cali back in the late 90's (SoCalRaves, Stormriders, ROAM, etc.) and  
am always interested in knowing what's going on with the EDM scene in  
my area.

Any information on good websites listing events and such would be  
greatly appreciated. Ravelinks seemed pretty sparse this last weekend  
or was there really that little going on?

Also, if anyone knows of job opportunities for a technical project  
manager, please let me know. Resume: http://resumes.hotjobs.com/ 
singinius/exptechpm

Ciao!

Nate

To respond to your question regarding websites that list events,
etc.... here are a few to get you going:

(these list mostly CLUB events, by the way, and most are 21+. To find
"real" raves I'd suggest Bayraves.com or staying tuned to this list.)


SFStation
http://sfstation.com/clubs/

Nitevibe
http://www.nitevibe.com/

Flavorpill
http://beta.sf.flavorpill.net/

Nitewise
http://www.nitewise.com/

SF Techno group on Upcoming.org
http://upcoming.org/group/780/


Can anyone think of any more you'd normally consult to find stuff
that's going on?


----->GB

tribe.net

MySpace

groundscore.net/board (breaks & drumNbass - but there's some other stuff 
posted from time to time too)

There are a TON of groups on MySpace & Tribe.net that cater specifically to 
the Bay Area and non-club events, as well as club stuff...

do a search forr my email addy: dj_marco138@hotmail.com on MySpace and send 
me an add request

or on Tribe, search under this address (electrofunk138@hotmail.com) for me.

Bcc: 
Date: Tue, 12 Sep 2006 16:58:03 -0700
Mime-Version: 1.0
Content-Type: text/plain; format=flowed
X-OriginalArrivalTime: 12 Sep 2006 23:58:08.0100 (UTC) FILETIME=[4B8CEA40:01C6D6C7]
X-Spam-Rating: taz3.hyperreal.org 1.6.2 0/1000/N
Subject: RE: [sfraves] Top 3 BM 2006 DJ's

Gotta love puttin out a subject like that.. Obvious IMHO - although I am a 
professional :)

There were three good DJ's at BM this year I thought that stood above the 
rest by a long way..

No really.. it's true!

1. DJ Adnan
2. Justin Martin
3. eDit (and the Glitch Mod Crew - okay so that 3 more)

Thursday night at around 9:30 & Esplanade (Gravity Point Camp) was this 
incredible enclave.. more like drippy funky ass, hard hitting cave of techno 
indulgence that left the dust on your skin turned to mud from the sweaty 
intoxicating beats that pulled me back in three times, only to leave for an 
under construction dome next door to hear more while getting laid on base 
bins.. damn I love BM.

These guys ripped the f&% out of the playa leaving nothing but groundscore.. 
now why are they on a house label when they hit it like that?? Dark freaky 
funky glitch and techno fused into an amalgamation of hard hitting breaks, 
sometimes with a jazzy riff, or trip-hop, or tribal changeup that left you 
breathless and gasping for air.  I was dancing on air at one point.. the 
beats lifting me ever higher until I was just on my tippie toes.. faining 
minimal gestures in the lightness of being the beats evoked.  Maybe it was 
the K.. I dunno.. but it was hot hot hot.. and I want me sa-mo!!!

Searching for more parties with these kids from SF where they shed their 
housy label and straight rip up the set with their OTHER records :)  Anyone 
got the word?


SFR: Ranger
San Francisco
plurranger@hotmail.com
Who knows where the night leads
It's dark and no one can see

>From: "Ranger -" <plurranger@hotmail.com>
>To: sfraves@hyperreal.org
>Subject: RE: [sfraves] Top 3 BM 2006 DJ's
>Date: Tue, 12 Sep 2006 16:58:03 -0700
>
>Gotta love puttin out a subject like that.. Obvious IMHO - although I am a 
>professional :)
>
>There were three good DJ's at BM this year I thought that stood above the 
>rest by a long way..
>
>No really.. it's true!
>
>1. DJ Adnan
>2. Justin Martin
>3. eDit (and the Glitch Mod Crew - okay so that 3 more)
>
>Thursday night at around 9:30 & Esplanade (Gravity Point Camp) was this 
>incredible enclave.. more like drippy funky ass, hard hitting cave of 
>techno indulgence that left the dust on your skin turned to mud from the 
>sweaty intoxicating beats that pulled me back in three times, only to leave 
>for an under construction dome next door to hear more while getting laid on 
>base bins.. damn I love BM.
>
>These guys ripped the f&% out of the playa leaving nothing but 
>groundscore.. now why are they on a house label when they hit it like 
>that?? Dark freaky funky glitch and techno fused into an amalgamation of 
>hard hitting breaks, sometimes with a jazzy riff, or trip-hop, or tribal 
>changeup that left you breathless and gasping for air.  I was dancing on 
>air at one point.. the beats lifting me ever higher until I was just on my 
>tippie toes.. faining minimal gestures in the lightness of being the beats 
>evoked.  Maybe it was the K.. I dunno.. but it was hot hot hot.. and I want 
>me sa-mo!!!
>
>Searching for more parties with these kids from SF where they shed their 
>housy label and straight rip up the set with their OTHER records :)  Anyone 
>got the word?
>
>
>SFR: Ranger
>San Francisco
>plurranger@hotmail.com
>Who knows where the night leads
>It's dark and no one can see

Diego & Portland. I'll pass the word along to the ones I know. :)

And yes, Adnan is right at the top. Didn't catch Justin or eDit, but yes, in
full agreement that they rock.

~juju

>
> Thursday night at around 9:30 & Esplanade (Gravity Point Camp) was this
> incredible enclave.. more like drippy funky ass, hard hitting cave of
> techno
> indulgence that left the dust on your skin turned to mud from the sweaty
> intoxicating beats that pulled me back in three times, only to leave for
> an
> under construction dome next door to hear more while getting laid on base
> bins.. damn I love BM.
>
> These guys ripped the f&% out of the playa leaving nothing but
> groundscore..
> now why are they on a house label when they hit it like that?? Dark freaky
> funky glitch and techno fused into an amalgamation of hard hitting breaks,
> sometimes with a jazzy riff, or trip-hop, or tribal changeup that left you
> breathless and gasping for air.  I was dancing on air at one point.. the
> beats lifting me ever higher until I was just on my tippie toes.. faining
> minimal gestures in the lightness of being the beats evoked.  Maybe it was
> the K.. I dunno.. but it was hot hot hot.. and I want me sa-mo!!!
