>incredible enclave.. more like drippy funky ass, hard hitting cave of 
>techno indulgence that left the dust on your skin turned to mud from the 
>sweaty intoxicating beats that pulled me back in three times, only to leave 
>for an under construction dome next door to hear more while getting laid on 
>base bins.. damn I love BM.
>
>These guys ripped the f&% out of the playa leaving nothing but 
>groundscore.. now why are they on a house label when they hit it like 
>that?? Dark freaky funky glitch and techno fused into an amalgamation of 
>hard hitting breaks, sometimes with a jazzy riff, or trip-hop, or tribal 
>changeup that left you breathless and gasping for air.  I was dancing on 
>air at one point.. the beats lifting me ever higher until I was just on my 
>tippie toes.. faining minimal gestures in the lightness of being the beats 
>evoked.  Maybe it was the K.. I dunno.. but it was hot hot hot.. and I want 
>me sa-mo!!!

> incredible enclave.. more like drippy funky ass, hard hitting cave of techno
> indulgence that left the dust on your skin turned to mud from the sweaty
> intoxicating beats that pulled me back in three times, only to leave for an
> under construction dome next door to hear more while getting laid on base
> bins.. damn I love BM.

Subject: Re: [sfraves] SF LoveFest 2006 - DJ Line Up

There's a big difference from doing something to make money and being in it "only" for the money.

I go to work to earn money.  If they didn't pay me I wouldn't show up.  But to say I'm "only" in it for the money wouldn't be right either.  I'm in it to pay the rent, feed my kids, have medicla insurance, buy records, etc.

On the other hand, there's a certain feeling that's obviously present when promoters primary interests are their wallets.  And then there are the extreme greed cases where advertised headliners are never booked, DJs and sound people aren't paid, and so forth.  I've certainly heard stories about this sort of behavior from some promoters but not Spundae or Skills.  I've actually witnessed it happen at one event.  (No I won't name names, but it was a large party in Miami.)

Which isn't the same thing as saying I love either crew's parties.  I've never been to a Skills party so I have no opinion, but I've been to some good and some bad Spundae events.

FWIW

Regards,

Peter

As a promoter, I will be honest and say I have been guilty of not paying DJ's and others involved in the party. Not becuase I wanted to burn anyone. It sucks, that feeling, but because I lost $10k on the party..... 
 
 I do have a problem with simply stating this person or that person is in it only for the money. I know Peter, and he loves what he does. Its a business for him, and in my eyes, there is nothing wrong with running a business. Why hate on him because he makes a living doing what he loves? Its stupid and immature. 
 
 There are bad promoters, call those promoters what they are. Don't just say that about anyone you don't know. 
 
 
 In a message dated 9/12/06 8:14:49 PM, dangrsmind@yahoo.com writes:
 
 
 There's a big difference from doing something to make money and being in it "only" for the money.
 
 I go to work to earn money.  If they didn't pay me I wouldn't show up.  But to say I'm "only" in it for the money wouldn't be right either.  I'm in it to pay the rent, feed my kids, have medicla insurance, buy records, etc.
 
 On the other hand, there's a certain feeling that's obviously present when promoters primary interests are their wallets.  And then there are the extreme greed cases where advertised headliners are never booked, DJs and sound people aren't paid, and so forth.  I've certainly heard stories about this sort of behavior from some promoters but not Spundae or Skills.  I've actually witnessed it happen at one event.  (No I won't name names, but it was a large party in Miami.)
 
 Which isn't the same thing as saying I love either crew's parties.  I've never been to a Skills party so I have no opinion, but I've been to some good and some bad Spundae events.
 
 FWIW
 
 Regards,
 
 Peter

From: <dangrsmind@yahoo.com>
Reply-To: dangrsmind@yahoo.com
To: Spinmylifeaway@aol.com, ericspire@yahoo.com, sfraves@hyperreal.org
Subject: Re: [sfraves] SF LoveFest 2006 - DJ Line Up
Date: Tue, 12 Sep 2006 20:14:38 -0700 (PDT)

There's a big difference from doing something to make money and being in it 
"only" for the money.

I go to work to earn money.  If they didn't pay me I wouldn't show up.  But 
to say I'm "only" in it for the money wouldn't be right either.  I'm in it 
to pay the rent, feed my kids, have medicla insurance, buy records, etc.

On the other hand, there's a certain feeling that's obviously present when 
promoters primary interests are their wallets.  And then there are the 
extreme greed cases where advertised headliners are never booked, DJs and 
sound people aren't paid, and so forth.  I've certainly heard stories about 
this sort of behavior from some promoters but not Spundae or Skills.  I've 
actually witnessed it happen at one event.  (No I won't name names, but it 
was a large party in Miami.)

Which isn't the same thing as saying I love either crew's parties.  I've 
never been to a Skills party so I have no opinion, but I've been to some 
good and some bad Spundae events.

FWIW

Regards,

Peter

Back in 2001 when I was at WMC we stayed at this cheap place by the beach called the Barbazon.  Pretty good deal, but not at all swanky. Its right across from the beach and the rooms have little kitchenettes.  Anyway, I was actually speaking at the conference that day (I was the least hung over person on the panel) and when I returned to the hotel Glaude was spinning in the lobby.  There were like 3 people there including me.  And it was free.  FWIW.

But I agree the expensive after party thing isn't where I'm at these days.  Not only because its sort of silly and lame, but also because I just spent $1500 on repairing my fricking car today.  Free/cheap is the way for me!

Peace,

Peter

that are headlining will ever play for free at the LoveFest parade.  They 
bring them in only to capitalize on the captive audience that didn't get 
enough of what was put on the event flyer.  They are in the lineup.. but 
they won't be at the event.  You will only get top see THEM if you pay!  
Now.. why??  Why can't THEY put down a freakin half hour or hour long set 
since we already paid them to come to the city and play a few hours later.. 
or at least some of them play. Why?

Busy schedules  afuckingside, I will whip out my ass for a "figurative" 
public spanking and eat all my criticism of the $ grubbing scene if 
Aphrodite spins one freakin track in public, or if Donald Glaude.. who I 
don't even like anymore since I saw him in a santa suit for a Christmas 
rave.. dunno.. just killed it.. spins on a float.  I bet Christopher 
Lawrence only plays for money.. and oh yes.. Oakenfold.. you will only see 
him in time for his set.. but he gets privilege as superstar DJ - not!

This whole thing started for me last year when that cocksuck Paul Van Dyke 
decided not to play because the event was asking for $5 donations.. so he 
didn't play the event.. but he sure as hell collected his cash and played 
the afterparty.  The AFTERPARTY is ruining the event by supplicating the 
talent to a pay for service model using the event as it's free ride.

It just bugs me.. my $.02

LoveFest does rule and should be supported no matter what the afterparty is 
about.. they have nothing in common.

From: <dangrsmind@yahoo.com>
Reply-To: dangrsmind@yahoo.com
To: Spinmylifeaway@aol.com, ericspire@yahoo.com, sfraves@hyperreal.org
Subject: Re: [sfraves] SF LoveFest 2006 - DJ Line Up
Date: Tue, 12 Sep 2006 20:14:38 -0700 (PDT)

There's a big difference from doing something to make money and being in it 
"only" for the money.

I go to work to earn money.  If they didn't pay me I wouldn't show up.  But 
to say I'm "only" in it for the money wouldn't be right either.  I'm in it 
to pay the rent, feed my kids, have medicla insurance, buy records, etc.

On the other hand, there's a certain feeling that's obviously present when 
promoters primary interests are their wallets.  And then there are the 
extreme greed cases where advertised headliners are never booked, DJs and 
sound people aren't paid, and so forth.  I've certainly heard stories about 
this sort of behavior from some promoters but not Spundae or Skills.  I've 
actually witnessed it happen at one event.  (No I won't name names, but it 
was a large party in Miami.)

Which isn't the same thing as saying I love either crew's parties.  I've 
never been to a Skills party so I have no opinion, but I've been to some 
good and some bad Spundae events.

FWIW

Regards,

Peter

dangrsmind@yahoo.com wrote:
> There's a big difference from doing something to make money and being in it "only" for the money.
>
> I go to work to earn money.  If they didn't pay me I wouldn't show up.  But to say I'm "only" in it for the money wouldn't be right either.  I'm in it to pay the rent, feed my kids, have medicla insurance, buy records, etc.
>
> On the other hand, there's a certain feeling that's obviously present when promoters primary interests are their wallets.  And then there are the extreme greed cases where advertised headliners are never booked, DJs and sound people aren't paid, and so forth.  I've certainly heard stories about this sort of behavior from some promoters but not Spundae or Skills.  I've actually witnessed it happen at one event.  (No I won't name names, but it was a large party in Miami.)
>
> Which isn't the same thing as saying I love either crew's parties.  I've never been to a Skills party so I have no opinion, but I've been to some good and some bad Spundae events.
>
> FWIW
>
> Regards,
>
> Peter

Subject: [sfraves]  ... on a postive note

On a positive note....

International DJ's will play for free.... Make
friends, and give them a chance to chill-out and
they'll have no problem...

Back in the day, when we did a local party on Friday
night, Doc, Terry Francis, Josh Wink, etc, would come
down for $0-$50.... If we made out well, they got paid
better, but no one cared if any money ever exchanged
hands... It was win/win or nothing/nothing....

If the intentions of the promoter are to break even at
best, MANY artists give bro-deals. If you are trying
to make mad money, the they should too.

E

PS... A lot of people were doing the nordic track at Tiesto

Subject: [sfraves] regarding lovefest

man, those were a lot of emails.

1)  ranger:  pvd didn't spin at THE afterparty.  he only spun at 1015
which was the PAM DJs afterparty.  PAM being a artist management group
that also was schedule to have a float in the parade that was supposed
to have PVD along with the other PAM DJs play.  that didn't happen, we
all heard about the drama, etc.

2)  the parade and the afterparty are two different events.  the
official afterparty is Spundae and Skills.  the parade is not.  there
are many people organizing the parade that are not in any way
affiliated with the official afterparty.  for example, both John Wood
of Somarts and Syd Gris of Opel are on the parade committee.  both are
also involved with the Love Infusion afterparty (with Tantra, Evil
Breaks and the Ambient Mafia) which is also in no way affiliated with
the official afterparty.

3)  on the page referenced in the original message:
http://www2.sflovefest.org/dj_line_up.php
it clearly says below that "Note: Not all artists appearing in
parade."  so there you have it.

4)  i think the donation wording thing is wack too.  but you pay to go
to Pride, pay to go to Castro on Halloween and pay for gas and parking
to go to Sunset at Lake Novato.  what else is new here?  hey, my crew
is paying $1500 for our float entry, a couple hundred to rent our
float, several hundred to decorate it and hours and hours of man
power.  shit, i wish i only had to pay $10 to come out and enjoy the
day!

and with that, i hope to see a bunch of you out there.  i'll be the DJ
about 30 feet in the air.  don't believe me?  come on out and see.

-- 
--------------------------
< Brandon / DJ Bam >

life ain't easy. Ha! Didn't see that comin, did ya? So I'll get right to

need to play "christian" music but can't have negative beats either. Any 
positive, uplifting, and spiritual music would be appreciated. We're in 
Central Oregon, Prineville to be exact. Of course would could pay travel 
expenses, but donated time would be appreciated. Anyone knowing of 
Oregon DJs with their eys on the Lord would be better. I'm just trying 
to throw some ideas together. For all I know the church may be willing 
to throw some real money at this but I need to know what we can do.

-HillBill

> There's a big difference from doing something to make money and being in 
> it "only" for the money.
>
> I go to work to earn money.  If they didn't pay me I wouldn't show up. 
> But to say I'm "only" in it for the money wouldn't be right either.  I'm 
> in it to pay the rent, feed my kids, have medicla insurance, buy records, 
> etc.
>
> On the other hand, there's a certain feeling that's obviously present when 
> promoters primary interests are their wallets.  And then there are the 
> extreme greed cases where advertised headliners are never booked, DJs and 
> sound people aren't paid, and so forth.  I've certainly heard stories 
> about this sort of behavior from some promoters but not Spundae or Skills.

man, those were a lot of emails.

1)  ranger:  pvd didn't spin at THE afterparty.  he only spun at 1015
which was the PAM DJs afterparty.  PAM being a artist management group
that also was schedule to have a float in the parade that was supposed
to have PVD along with the other PAM DJs play.  that didn't happen, we
all heard about the drama, etc.

2)  the parade and the afterparty are two different events.  the
official afterparty is Spundae and Skills.  the parade is not.  there
are many people organizing the parade that are not in any way
affiliated with the official afterparty.  for example, both John Wood
of Somarts and Syd Gris of Opel are on the parade committee.  both are
also involved with the Love Infusion afterparty (with Tantra, Evil
Breaks and the Ambient Mafia) which is also in no way affiliated with
the official afterparty.

3)  on the page referenced in the original message:
http://www2.sflovefest.org/dj_line_up.php
it clearly says below that "Note: Not all artists appearing in
parade."  so there you have it.

4)  i think the donation wording thing is wack too.  but you pay to go
to Pride, pay to go to Castro on Halloween and pay for gas and parking
to go to Sunset at Lake Novato.  what else is new here?  hey, my crew
is paying $1500 for our float entry, a couple hundred to rent our
float, several hundred to decorate it and hours and hours of man
power.  shit, i wish i only had to pay $10 to come out and enjoy the
day!

and with that, i hope to see a bunch of you out there.  i'll be the DJ
about 30 feet in the air.  don't believe me?  come on out and see.

Thats' fucked up.

See, I was one of the guys in black shirts on security detail.  I was on 
Gate 7, 8, 9 doing the money drops.  We had guys on the gates as well.  We 
wern't there just for the crowd, we were watching everything.  However with 
our crew of 150 and over 100,000 attendee's all day, we couldn't see 
everything.

My advice to everyone when you go to something like Love Parade...  if you 
see some staffer who's suppose dto be doing gate collection pocket money, 
let the security guys know.  If one blows you off, tell another.  They're 
not all perfect, but 9/10th of the guys are serious about what they do and 
it will be dealt with.  You may not see it, but it will happen.  If we have 
a heads up then we can catch the person doing it and then take them to the 
promoter and let them ask why they are pocketing money at the gate.

That really pisses me off.

Also, from the security side, all day and all night we only had one arrest 
we had to deal with.  Quite a few medical issues though, mainly from people 
going all day in the sun and forgeting to properly hydrate 
themselves.  Rememeber, BEER is not water!  Drink your water, lots of it.

The Glass is half empty I see...

How about a Half Full approch..

You throw and all day party in which people can choose to support or not 
support, and enjoy either way.  You go all day and into the night.

Then!

You throw a high price event at night for the dumbasses that will actually 
pay it, and in return, cover the costs for the free daytime event all your 
friends got to have a blast at.

Don't know if this was the case...  but it's what I would do, and have 
done, and will do.  You do something that pulls in money, and you do it for 
money, so that you can have the capital to pay for fun events for your 
friends and such and not worry about going bankrupt.  Anything really wrong 
with that?

I mean, isn't that what all the Burning Man "fund raisers" and compression 
parties are all about anyway?

Thats' fucked up.

See, I was one of the guys in black shirts on security detail.  I was on 
Gate 7, 8, 9 doing the money drops.  We had guys on the gates as well.  We 
wern't there just for the crowd, we were watching everything.  However with 
our crew of 150 and over 100,000 attendee's all day, we couldn't see 
everything.

My advice to everyone when you go to something like Love Parade...  if you 
see some staffer who's suppose dto be doing gate collection pocket money, 
let the security guys know.  If one blows you off, tell another.  They're 
not all perfect, but 9/10th of the guys are serious about what they do and 
it will be dealt with.  You may not see it, but it will happen.  If we have 
a heads up then we can catch the person doing it and then take them to the 
promoter and let them ask why they are pocketing money at the gate.

That really pisses me off.

Also, from the security side, all day and all night we only had one arrest 
we had to deal with.  Quite a few medical issues though, mainly from people 
going all day in the sun and forgeting to properly hydrate 
themselves.  Rememeber, BEER is not water!  Drink your water, lots of it.

> Own it.  I also have many other tracks that are about enlightenment 
> "God" and so forth.  But I also have some about sex and drugs.  Does 
> that make me bad?

Never said it did, just said I was trying to stay away from the for this 
particular event. There's similar stuff in my crate too.

> "Good kids" generally do't go to raves ya know?  I guess this means 
> they don't do drugs (fine)

According to the media they do. That's all the good kids turned lying 
drug addicts by evil "rave parties," according to Diane Sawyer. Excuse 
the sarcasm the media drives me nuts but I said party, wasn't calling it 
a rave. And why can't good kids have a safe and positive night with 
their friends?

> and they don't have sex, or rather they don't admit to having sex.

Everyone stumbles in their walk with the Lord. The important part is to 
get back up. Not perfect just forgiven. We try to encourage our youth to 
wait until marriage but no one is going to love them any less if they 
don't.

> I'm skeptical, but OK, I'm open minded.  You realize that Buddhists 
> don't believe in a personal God right?  We're practically Satanists.  
> Or so I was told by the Jehovah's witnesses that came to my house a few 
> weeks back.  Buddhists do pray sort of, but not to "God".

My Magic, Witchcraft and Religion anthropology class was a while back 
but yes I'm fairly familiar with Buddhist beliefs and ideals. I would 
never call you a satanist, nor do I go door to door pushing my faith. If 
you're curious I'll speak to you about my faith (understanding is key) 
and yes I've ministered to friends and need, but door to door faith 
ain't my style.

Problem is that all I wanted was some referals and you want to turn this 
into some religious debate and I'm really not interested. If you want 
some "christians" to argue with I'm sure there are plenty outside your 
local abortion clinic, just look for their signs and listening for their 
yelling.

> Actually for the record, I'm a tantric Buddhist which means that I 
> believe in using delusion, attachment, and other so called "negative" 
> energies as tools of enlightenment.  That includes sexual energy, 
> anger, violence, or whatever there is.   We work with what we've got 
> and bring it onto the path.

Not much different than my faith. Suffering isn't such a bad thing, to 
experience pain is to know what Jesus went through. I pray when things 
are good and when they're bad. It's all a part of life.

> See I thought you were talking about beats that were 180 degrees out of 
> phase thereby destructively cancelling out the regular "positive 
> beats".  ;)

No that would be bad.

> I don't see sex as a negative thing at all.  I think its interesting 
> that you lump sexual lyrics in with violent lyrics.  See my comments 
> about tantra above.  Last time I checked Christians did actually have 
> sex, or else there wouldn't be too many of them around.  My wife's 
> friend who is a practicing Catholic has seven kids.  I don't think the 
> stork brought them, do you?

I wasn't lumping anything, I was making a list of that which I did not 
want at the event. And you're right, we do have sex but only through a 
hole in the sheet.

> Spawing is  a sexual reference!

Yep, to fish.

Peas!
-HillBill

The person known to most folks as Jesus Christ would never judge ANYONE 
based on what they listened to, danced to, what drugs they ate, or any other 
superficial factor. He would base his judgements upon the character of their 
soul.

To deny people these things, or deny letting them decide for themseleves 
whether or not they want that sort of content in their lives (or music), is, 
well...not very Jesus like.

WWJD? He'd laugh at the vast majority of Christians making decisions "in his 
name".

PLUR!

On my mission to avoid depression I have gotten into RC cars since I'm
currently taking a break from music until my album is released. I got a hi
end electric and damn this thing is insane. ~45 mph, goes so fast that the
only place big enough to drive it is on my street. My apartment complex
backyard is paved and about 50 sq yards in size, but even that isn't really
big enough. I never knew how fast these things had gotten. Also, building it
was harder then putting a turbo on my prelude. You really have to study this
stuff in order to do it right.

The car is a Tamiya Evolution 5. Fun shit.

http://www.SlumberMachine.com

CD called in the House of God.  Thinking it was just some collection of
House tracks.  It was Christian house.  Some of the beats were fucking sick,
but there would be this gospel, god like singing on top of it.  It was
hillarios as shit, specially driving up to Seattle for a party when he first
got it, and we were doing lines of meth on the way up and he's all hey i got
this new CD lets listen to it......Oh My God....that shit was hialrious.


So remember kids, the northwest is only good for Meth and when you thing
yours in the House of God you're really in God's house and even God needs a
little more cowbell once in a while.

Subject: [sfraves] BSP: NaturallyII :: ILL BEHAVIOR 5YR Anniversary :: 9/30 -1 0/01

"So.... almost 5 years ago, at about this time, in a woodsy setting 
overlooking our beautiful bay...a number of us got swerved and rocked beats 
until the sun came up. We've done it again since then and we'll do it again 
many times, but we thought 5 years was a mighty fine anniversary to toast 
to...so heres what I'm sippin as I raise my glass with all you 
inappropriate, wretched assholes." ~ Kris Kent

The ill behavior family and a motley group of friends welcomes you to...

Naturally II - "5 years of bad decisions and broken curfews"

'an outdoor gathering in a beautiful NorCal setting'
Saturday September 30th - Sunday October 1st
12 noon til 12 noon
FREE as can be!!!!

Expect Choice music, certified loonies, camping and running amok.

Capacity is limited and this one's gonna be huge, so don't be late!


Saturday, September 16

[ K O N T R O L ]

minimal techno + avant house
every 3rd Saturday at Rx Gallery


featuring from Glasgow, Scotland:

===>  ALEX SMOKE - live!  <===

( Soma . Vakant . Crosstown Rebels . Trapez . Ware )

Hot off a headlining performance at Seattle's Decibel Festival,
Alex Smoke brings his achingly lush, musical, and emotive
techno to San Francisco for the first time ever. Hear for yourself
why the young lad from Glasgow has become and international
sensation in just two short years.


plus special guest:

===>  JUSTIN MARTIN  <===

( Dirtybird . Classic . Buzzin' Fly . Om )

One year after his unforgettable performance opening for Isolee,
San Francisco's brightest young producer and DJ returns with
what's sure to be another jaw-dropping set crafted especailly
for KONTROL.


with resident DJs:

ALLAND BYALLO  ( liebe*detail . kvadrat produkt . mo's ferry )
SAMMY D  ( classic . dirtybird . utensil )
CRAIG KUNA    ( concept sf . esdjco )

________________________________________________

Rx Gallery
132 Eddy @ Mason, SF / 415.474.7973
9pm-2am / 21+ / $10
http://www.rxgallery.com

limited capacity, arrive early to assure entry!

________________________________________________


Full bios, pics and lots FREE music!
http://www.kontrolsf.com

______________________________________________


Biography: ALEX SMOKE

Alex Smoke is unique talent to emerge from the Glasgow music scene. This
young producer is pushing the boundaries of electronic music with his
innovative fusion of deep European minimalism with emotional strings and
intellegent electro rhythms. Alex has a classical music background which
reveals itself in the quality of his arrangements. In the past two years the
music world has witnessed his rapid ascent through the ranks of the techno
elite. Since the 2005 release of his brilliant debut LP on Soma,
'Incommunicado' he has been booked to play the clubs and festivals of the
UK, Europe and beyond. His coveted releases on Berlin label Vakant have
cemented his club credentials and found their way into boxes and laptops of
innovative DJs everywhere. Not content with a slew of killer twelves, Alex
Smoke remixes have constantly been in demand, recently renovating Mylo, Alex
Under and Vector Lovers. 2006 has shaped up to be another monumental one for
Alex Smoke with the release of his second LP, 'Paradolia' and subsequent UK,
European, and US live tours.

website:
http://www.somarecords.com/artists/alexsmoke/

discography:
http://www.discogs.com/artist/Alex%20Smoke

Alex Smoke - Don't See The Point (mp3 sample):
http://mp3.juno.co.uk/MP3/SF198216-01-01-02.mp3

Alex Smoke - Meany (mp3 sample):
http://mp3.juno.co.uk/MP3/SF210583-01-01-01.mp3

___________________________________________

Biography: JUSTIN MARTIN

Justin Martin is one of the few house DJs that successfully bridges the gap
between being commercially successful and staying true to the underground.
His sound has been described as both melodic and tough, with releases
ranging from the dynamic "Cicada" on dirtybird to the slamming "Magnificent"
remix for Iz and Diz on OM records.  Justin first gained international
acclaim for his single, "The Sad Piano," on Ben Watt's Buzzin'fly label. The
single made its way into many A-List DJ crates as well as receiving many
accolades from critics. Over time, Justin developed a more edgy sound in his
hometown of San Francisco. He helped develop the local dirtybird label with
his good friend, Claude VonStroke, releasing several amazing singles and
remixes. Justin considers himself lucky to be making music and is always a
humble, but rocking presence on the dance floor. Stay tuned for some amazing
collaborations with his brother Christian coming soon on dirtybird as well
as a mix compilation on the Om Winter Sessions Series.

website:
http://www.dirtybirdrecords.com/justin_martin.html

discography:
http://www.discogs.com/artist/Justin%20Martin

promo dj mix (feb 2006):
http://www.dirtybirdrecords.com/audio/mixes/take_me_out.mp3


__________________________________________


Coming next month:

AKUFEN ( Musique Risque . Perlon . Mutek_Rec // Montreal )


http://www.kontrolsf.com

Courtesy of my boy EVINRUDE:

Hi!
We've got some great stuff going on this week, first with the Ferrets being 
joined by the Strategik Breaks crew at Crooked, then with the Space Cowboys 
tearing it up with a stellar local lineup at DNA Friday, and then of course 
there's Love Fest, and finally with the Mog throwing down outside Seismic's 
After the Love (with Deekline and Wizard, and Nick Thayer, inside!) at 
Mighty on Saturday. Love Fest weekend is finally here, and we're really 
busy, and we can't wait!
-Evan

+++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

TOMORROW!!!!!! (9/20) - the STRATEGIK crew will be reppin' it on 9/20, so 
make sure and catch the sounds they'll be dropping at their Love Fest 
float/afterparty! (Love Infusion)

Crooked happens @ Nickie's BBQ
460 Haight St. @ Fillmore, SF
10pm-2am
$3, 21+ with ID


9/20:
Ill-D
Jay Vigor
Influence
Marc(O)

CROOKED happens EVERY Wednesday night @ NICKIE'S!!!!

GET BENT!!!


+++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++


Fri, 9/22  SPACE COWBOYS present COWBOYS AND ALIENS @ DNA LOUNGE

Space Cowboys are kicking off this year's LOVEFEST in our own intergalactic 
fashion. For this party we've got a bunch of your favorite Space Cowboy DJs, 
and brought in some of our favorite local alien DJs to join the fun.


In the Main Room

Brad Robinson -vs- Murphstar

Mancub -vs- Kapt'n Kirk

8-Ball -vs- Shissla

Rrrus -vs- Shooey



In the Lounge

Aaron Jae -vs- Melyss

Ernie Trevino -vs- Evinrude



DNA Lounge  375 11th Street, SF

10pm - 4am / 21+

$5 b4 midnight & $10 after.

$5 in Alien costume


+++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++

Fri, 9/23  SEISMIC presents AFTER THE LOVE @ MIGHTY

For the third year in a row, SEISMIC is throwing the Breaks After party for 
the San Francisco Love Parade/Fest. AFTER The Love, will have three huge 
sound systems and caollection of international superstar DJ's, Local 
favorites and special guests. Doors open at 10:00 and the party will keep 
rockin till 5:00.



Headliners: Deekline & Wizard (Bounce / Rat Records, UK), Nick Thayer 
(Breaking Point, Aus) Local Heroes: Murphstar (SEISMIC) Samira (SEISMIC), 
Trav (SEISMIC) Brett Pinkin (SEISMIC), Emerge (Disfunktion Crew, BreaksFM )

Club Bootie laying down mash ups and bootlegs in the Back! 
(www.BootieSF.com)

Special Guests: The Space Cowboys with the UNIMOG Rocking the Block in front



Mighty - 119 Utah St

10:00 PM - 5:00 AM / 21+

Limited $10 pre-sale tickets available at: (http://www.seismicsf.org) or 
www.groovetickets.com

$20 at the door.

route!  http://local.live.com

ADAM GOLDSTONE // REST IN PEACE

<http://djsake1.c.topica.com/maafaK2abto72b7EP2ceaehn6P/>Adam Goldstone passed away from heart failure, stemming from a congenital heart defect, on August 29, 2006. He was 37 years young. 

The bitterness of his loss is tempered by the fact that Adam passed preparing to do what he loved -- play music and build community -- at the <http://djsake1.c.topica.com/maafaK2abto73b7EP2ceaehn6P/>Burning Man festival, which he fell in love with in 2005 when he first went.

Adam's mission was love, and his method was music. Make and play music, spread love, stay true to yourself...<http://djsake1.c.topica.com/maafaK2abto75b7EP2ceaehn6P/>remember Adam!!!  

For a (nearly) complete Adam Goldstone discography, click <http://djsake1.c.topica.com/maafaK2abto91b7EP2ceaehn6P/>HERE. If you would like to join the family in honoring and remembering Adam, we set up a <http://djsake1.c.topica.com/maafaK2abto72b7EP2ceaehn6P/>Myspace page in his memory. To read comments from his NYC and clubland homies, check <http://djsake1.c.topica.com/maafaK2abto92b7EP2ceaehn6P/>this and <http://djsake1.c.topica.com/maafaK2abto93b7EP2ceaehn6P/>this out...beyond NYC, he got love <http://djsake1.c.topica.com/maafaK2abto94b7EP2ceaehn6P/>all over the world, cuz he went there and played music. He also was a dope <file:// http://westendrecords.com/artists/larry_bio.php3>writer.

To hear an incredible live mix from the Detroit Electronic Music Festival (c. 2003), click <http://djsake1.c.topica.com/maafaK2abto95b7EP2ceaehn6P/>HERE. There's another mix <http://www.wps1.org/include/shows/wps1_DJ_sessions.html>here. 

There will be a memorial party for Adam on November 14, 2006 at <http://djsake1.c.topica.com/maafaK2abtpbwb7EP2ceaehn6P/>Cielo in NYC, featuring Adam's favorite DJs, as well as his huge extended family and community. Please join us if you can... 
His family appreciates all the support and love we have gotten from everyone -- way too many to name, but we remember and thank each of you. If you would like to make a donation in Adam's memory, we suggest <http://djsake1.c.topica.com/maafaK2abtpbCb7EP2ceaehn6P/>Loisaida, Inc, which works on behalf of Adam's beloved Lower East Side/Alphabet City neighbors, or the <http://djsake1.c.topica.com/maafaK2abtpbFb7EP2ceaehn6P/>ACLU. 





http://www.asambleapopulardeoaxaca.com/ 

MySpace:  http://www.myspace.com/DJApollo 

Tribenet:   <http://people.tribe.net/djapollo2k>http://people.tribe.net/djapollo2k 
                
House Music 101:  http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm

"Americans like to talk about (or be told about) Democracy but, when put to the test, usually find it to be an 'inconvenience.' We have opted instead for an authoritarian system disguised as a Democracy. We pay through the nose for an enormous joke-of-a-government, let it push us around, and then wonder how all those assholes got in there." - Frank Zappa 

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of the rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will gradually become visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

Outdoor Surf Movie Night   September 20, 2006 06:30 PM - 09:30 AM

This Wednesday, September 20, bring your blankets, beach chairs,  dogs, 
movie pals and the kids down to Park Chalet's grassy lawn by  Ocean Beach!

Salt Water Cinema kicks off *FREE* Outdoor Surf Movie Night series  with the 
campy 1987 surf cult classic, North Shore (rated PG) and the  trailer for 
One Winter Story, the documentary on Maverick's first  female surfer, Sarah 
Gerhardt. Enjoy live music by Drifting Sand at  6:30pm, plus a special Park 
Chalet outdoor grill menu of food, beer,  margaritas & hot drinks. Show 
starts at dusk, about 7:30 pm.

Catch some good Hawaiian surf footage & see *young* Laird Hamilton,
Occy, and other pros on our 10x20 outdoor screen.

Arrive early for best seating under the Indian Summer stars and heat lamps! 
For more info, visit http://www.surfmovienight.com
Park Chalet's grassy lawn 1000 Great Highway
at Ocean Beach (back of Beach Chalet) San Francisco, CA 94121

Wednesday, 9/20, 7:30-9:30 -- EROTIC READING CIRCLE
At Jon Sims Center, 1519 Mission St @ 11th St. in SF

Come join readers as they share their work! Bring something to read  or just 
be part of the appreciative circle of listeners. This is a  great place to 
try out new work (ask for comments if you  like), or  get more comfortable 
reading for other people. Longtime writers will  bring thier latest... newly 
inspired writers, bring that vignette you  scrawled on BART while 
daydreaming on your way to work! Non- judgemental listening guaranteed, all 
orientations welcome. With  Carol Queen and Jennifer Cross.
$5-up sliding scale, but no one turned away for lack of funds.

-----------------------------------------------------------

POWERDOWN     Inspired by Jan Lundberg
http://www.culturechange.org 215-243-3144

If the U.S. continues with its current policies, the next decades  will be 
marked by war, economic collapse, and environmental  catastrophe. Resource 
depletion and population pressures are about to  catch up with us, and no 
one is prepared. The political elites,  especially in the U.S., are 
incapable of dealing with the situation  and have in mind a punishing game 
of Last One Standing. The  alternative is Powerdown, a strategy that 
will require tremendous  effort and economic sacrifice in order to reduce 
per-capita resource  usage in wealthy countries, develop alternative energy 
sources,  distribute resources more equitably, and reduce the human 
population  humanely but systematically over time. While civil society  
organizations push for a mild version of this, the vast majority of  the 
worlds people are in the dark, not understanding the challenges  ahead, nor 
the options realistically available. This film speaks  frankly to these 
dilemmas. Avoiding cynicism and despair, it begins  with an overview of the 
likely impacts of oil and natural gas  depletion and then outlines four 
options for industrial societies  during the next decades: Last One 
Standing: the path of competition  for remaining resources; Powerdown: the 
path of cooperation,  conservation and sharing; Waiting for a Magic Elixir: 
wishful  thinking, false hopes, and denial; Building Lifeboats: the path of  
community solidarity and preservation. Timely, accessible and  eloquent, 
POWERDOWN is crucial information for our times. This is a  film presentation 
by Richard Heinberg of his own recent book by the  same name.
http://store.solarlivingstore.com/powerdown.html

Before and after the film, everyones invited to indulge in our  Humanist 
Tea House
$5 donations are accepted  September 20, 2006 Starts at 07:30 PM
Humanist Hall 390 27th St Oakland, CA 94612 (btwn Telegraph / Broadway)
Additional Event Information  510-393-5685
http://www.HumanistHall.net http://laughingsquid.com/squidlist/events
http://laughingsquid.com/squidlist/events/index.php? 
com=detail&eID=7031&year=2006&month=09

THIS Wednesday "FOOD JUSTICE" free showing
9/20 come catch this 20 min. food flick wednite 8pm, it's fresh and  locally 
grown ;-)

A film showing of "FOOD JUSTICE: A Growing Movement" will occur at
Station 40 (3030b 16th Street) free of charge on wednesday evening
(the 20th of September, 2006), most likely starting at 8pm *do
remember that the movie is only 20 minutes, so come too late and you
WILL miss it, although there'll probably be another good one playing
afterwards*.
Please attend if you would like to see Alemany Farm in action, and its
volunteers smile, and even speak, on camera.

-----
Here's a blurb-y type thing about the movie:

"Martina Brimmer and Zora Tucker set out to tell the story of unequal
access to food in our urban minority communities as a symptom of
environmental racism and classism.

The extraordinary vision of various organizations in west oakland and
san francisco brings to light the spirit of the food justice movement.

Striving to cultivate justice in their neighborhoods and nourish their
communities, groups such as Oakland Based Urban Gardens, People's
Grocery, Mandela's Market and the volunteers of the Alemany Farm are
confronting social, agricultural and environmental issues that affect
us all.

FOOD JUSTICE: A GROWING MOVEMENT was conceptualized in a cafe in
Prescott, Arizona by two strangers, Zora Tucker and Martina Brimmer.
The project was formally Martina's Senior Project, but instantly
became a mutual adventure as Zora quit her job to accompany Martina.
Neither of them had so much as made home-videos, much less attempted
to document an issue which called for articulate exposure.
The two felt that the issues of urban food security and their
relationship to systemic oppression, environmental racism, health
issues and the failure of our conventional food system needed to reach
the public, with primary distribution within the communities that bear
the consequences of social inequity. It was also their intention as
activists to portray the world which they are striving to create, and
so Martina and Zora focused upon several of many Bay Area grassroots
projects that they feel are the food justice movement."

Talk about sex at One Taste  Wednesday, September 20   8:00 PM
Imagine this: A room full of turned on people with their full  attention on 
you. They raise their hands, the facilliator calls on  them, and they get to 
ask you a question on any topic on any level of  intensity.

"What is your favorite sexual position?"
"What turns you on?"
"What makes you the most jealous?"

You've got three options - (a) Tell the truth, (b) Lie, or (c) refuse  to 
answer. Just like life. What would you do?

Come experience this and more at the InSight Institute's weekly IN  Group. 
At these groups, we play structured communication games aimed  at you having 
more intimacy and fun in your life. Can you imagine a  life full of 
pleasure? Come and find out how. Singles, couples,  friends, communities, 
and more invited.

When: Thursday nights: 7:45pm to 10:30pm
Cost: $10 sliding scale
Contact: 415.503.1100 - http://www.InSightInstitute.net
Where: Hosted by One Taste Urban Retreat Center 1074 Folsom at 7th  Street
===========================================

PARK(ing) Day 2006
Thursday, September 21, 2006 - Sunday, September 21, 2008
10:00 AM
PARK(ing) Day is this Thursday ,September 21st!

REBAR opened eyes worldwide by temporarily transforming a metered  parking 
spot into a PARK. We reclaimed the street for peopleat least  until the 
meter ran out!

Now the challenge is up to you.
REBAR, with support from The Trust for Public Land (TPL) want you,  the most 
creative minds in San Francisco and around the globe, to  create the most 
innovative PARK in a parking spot.

Please join us as we transform parking spots into PARK(ing) spaces:  
temporary public parks in areas that need open space  enlivening the  
streets and improving the quality of urban human habitat.

more info http://www.rebargroup.org/projects/parkingday

Love Fest This Week!

Hello Lovers!
The wait for one of the parties of the year is almost over.
LoveWeek is here! All of us at Love HQ can hardly contain our  excitement 
over all the fun in store for the city and the scene. For  starters, we're 
proud to announce the original founder of Loveparade  Berlin, Dr. Motte, 
will be our special guest to give a keynote speech  to kick off the parade 
at 12 noon on Saturday. What better way to  start the the next evolution of 
love in America? We thought so too!
LoveWeek starts this Wednesday at a special Sooper Qool LoveFest  edition of 
the famous Qool happy hour located at 111 Minna @ 2nd.
Thursday we dine and dance at Supperclub with a dinner starting at  7:30pm 
and dance afterwards starting around 11pm. Supperclub is at  657 Harrison 
St. @ 2nd. Reservations for dinner still available.
Friday night we have the Official LoveFest pre-party, presented by  Opel and 
Lee Coombs. Thrust for Love will feature 3 areas of sound,  with Lee Coombs 
and locals stars, and will be at Mighty: 119 Utah St.  @ 15th.
Saturday floats start to gather at 2nd and Market at ~11am, sound  fires up 
at 11:30, and we kick it off at 12 noon. Please come see the  keynote 
address by Dr. Motte, a true visionary of dance culture.
The Official LoveFest after party Spundae and Skills after party will  be on 
the doorstep of the festival and features 3 rooms of world  class talent 
including Paul Oakenfold, Christopher Lawrence, Bad Boy  Bill, DJ Dan, 
Dieselboy, and much much more!
And Sunday, when you haven't had enough, head down to the End Up for  the 
LoveFest closing party presented by theendup and listedsf, in  association 
with Funkycozy and satellitesf. Wow!

PEACE WALK and Evening Musical Jam
Host: Eah Herren and Ross Holzman
Location: Alamo Square Park
Steiner and Hayes, San Francisco, CA View Map
When: Thursday, September 21, 8:00am
Thursday, September 21st is the International Day of Peace.

Please Join us for a Celebration; a Peace Walk through San Francisco  and an 
evening of Music and Merriment at the SOMA Creativity Center.

PEACE WALK Schedule of Events:

8am > Gather at Alamo Square Park for Morning Meditation, Movement
and Music.

10am> Peace Walk departs for Golden Gate Park, passing through the
Panhandle.

10.30> Gathering at Hippy Hill in Golden Gate Park.
We will then make our way down the Haight.

12 noon> Assembly at Civic Center for a pause, gathering friends and
playing music.

1.30pm> Meditation at Union Square.

3pm> Gathering in Delores Park for Closing Ceremony; prayer,
music and refreshments.

Please contact Eah (415-722-4282) or Ross (415-385-4065) for details  
regarding the Peace Walk, your participation, and/or joining us along  the 
way.

BIRTHDAY CELEBRATION and MUSICAL PERFORMANCE

7-11pm> Following this day of prayer and peaceful intention, we will  gather 
for an evening of Musical Performance featuring the Birthday  Girl, Eah, 
along with her fabulous crew of talented Musicians for  dance and continued 
celebration.

The Evening Gathering and Birthday Celebration will occur at:

The SOMA Creativity Center
81 Langton St. Suite 13
(Langton is located between 7th and 8th St, off of Folsom St, next to  
Brainwash.)
San Francisco, CA 94103

We look forward to seeing you there!

9/21: 6pm:   1906 SF Earthquake - 3D Presentation & Book Signing
"Stereoviewing 1906: The San Francisco Earthquake in 3-D" by David  
Burkhardt
Special 3-D Presentation & Book Signing
California Historical Society - Gallery
678 Mission St., @ 3rd St / 2nd St. San Francisco
6 p.m. - Admission is FREE

David Burkhardt, author of "The 1906 San Francisco Earthwuake in 3-D"  will 
be at the California Historical Society to make a unique  presentation! 
Stereo cameras and viewers were all the rage at the  turn of the century and 
David Burkehardt has exhibited in his book  some of the best stereo 
photographs of the 1906 earthquake.

Also, 1906 earthquake survivor, Herbert Hamerol (age 103) will be  joining 
us! He will be available to answer questions about the 1906  happenings 
after the presentation.

Arrive early for this can't miss evening to get a good seat and a  pair of 
3-D glasses!

For more information about this event and the California Historical Society, 
please visit our website at http:// californiahistoricalsociety.org or call 
415.357.1848, ext. 229.
http://sfbay.craigslist.org/eve/203205250.html

Dellums won. What happens next is up to us. JOIN US 9/21 6-9pm Oakland

Breaking Our Addiction to Oil?
New Jobs in Green Construction?
Energy Independence for Oakland?
Is the new environmentally-sustainable economy strong enough to lift  
Oakland's people out of poverty? Can Oakland become the nation's  leading 
"green-collar" city?

The Oakland Apollo Alliance presents a
SOLUTIONS SALON on "Green-Collar Jobs"

Featuring Aya de Leon, Nancy Nadel, Van Jones, and more!

WHEN:
Thursday, September 21
6 - 7pm: Reception and light food (please bring your own cup and  eating 
utensils, if possible)
7 - 9pm: Discussion

WHERE:
Laney College Theatre
900 Fallon Street, Oakland, CA (near Lake Merritt BART Station)
Laney College Campus Map:
http://laney.peralta.edu/apps/page.asp?Q=TheatreMap&menutab=13
Co-sponsored by the Peralta Community College District

WHAT IS A SOLUTIONS SALON?

Dialogue. Inspiration. Community. A "Solutions Salon" is more than  your 
typical panel discussion. It's a chance to ask hard questions  and deal 
thoughtfully with some of Oakland's biggest problems... and  opportunities. 
For this event, we'll be discussing "Green-Collar"  jobs: Can Oakland become 
a national leader in providing living-wage  jobs in environmentally friendly 
enterprises? Join us and be part of  the solution!

WHAT IS THE OAKLAND APOLLO ALLIANCE?

The Oakland Apollo Alliance is a coalition of labor unions,  
environmentalists, and community organizations working to create high  
quality jobs in the modern energy economy, revitalize underserved  
communities and improve the environment.

The Oakland Apollo Alliance is co-convened and staffed by the Ella  Baker 
Center for Human Rights and IBEW Local 595. For more about the  event and 
the Oakland Apollo Alliance, e-mail Ian Kim at ian @  ellabakercenter.org

Not on our list-serve yet? Sign up to get e-mail updates directly by going 
to http://www.ellabakercenter.org/subscribe

Subject: [sfraves] Newsweek: Poor but Sexy

This story from Newsweek strikes a chord as we get ready to celebrate our l=
ittle local version of the Love  Parade....

Peter



Berlin's coolest new club, Kubik, hides behind an unmarked gate across from=
 a crumbling house full of squatters in a derelict downtown lot on the rive=
r Spree. It's built entirely from refashioned industrial containers emanati=
ng a translucent green light. If they seem to be almost alive, it's no acci=
dent; thanks to an edgy software interface, they pulsate to DJ Bobby Fr=C3=
=B6hlich's smooth post-techno beats. Amid the occasional sweet scent of can=
nabis, crowds of twentysomethings party until dawn. Sic transit Gloria Mund=
i . This weekend the cubes will be taken down and, poof, Kubik will be no m=
ore.

 =20
    Quirky, creative and outrageously cheap--the cover charge is but a sing=
le euro, and beers cost =E2=82=AC2--Kubik is a perfect metaphor for the new=
 Berlin. Remember all that post-unification speculation that the city, as a=
 rising Germany's new capital, would metamorphose from a gritty outpost of =
the cold war into yet another homogenized, prosperous Eurotropolis? Forget =
it. The post-unity boom has fizzled--and most Berliners are perfectly happy=
 about it.

=20
    Once again, their city is both Germany's undisputed lifestyle capital--=
and worst economic laggard. Judging by the bustling caf=C3=A9s, thriving ar=
t galleries and ubiquitous club scene (think Kubik, squared), you'd never k=
now that Berlin suffers from nearly 20 percent unemployment. Per capita inc=
ome is the lowest of any major German city. The economy has shrunk by 10 pe=
rcent over the last decade, and the city's public debt, amounting to some =
=E2=82=AC80 billion, is more than that of Peru, Ecuador and Guatemala combi=
ned. Kubik is a symbol of all this, too. After all, the lot on which it sta=
nds, free of charge, has been on the market for nearly 15 years--prime down=
town riverside real estate that can't find takers at one fifth what it woul=
d cost in London.

=20
    All this would be a cause of outrage in most world cities. Yet Berliner=
s are at ease. Most were tickled when Klaus Wowereit, their popular partygo=
ing mayor, dubbed the town "poor but sexy" late last year. A Social Democra=
t governing in coalition with the communists, the openly gay 52-year-old is=
 a shoo-in to win Berlin's Sept. 17 election. His opponent, a sober-suited =
conservative, gets zero traction. Why? Because Wowi, as he's called, has ma=
naged to finesse the mess. Though nearly bankrupt, the city has kept budget=
 cutbacks small enough to avoid angering voters. That's important, given th=
at a whopping 41 percent of Berliners live off government subsidies--pensio=
ns, welfare, unemployment--and that the city's 200,000 civil servants make =
up one of the municipality's biggest voting blocs. And so what if that Kafk=
aesque bureaucracy is infamous for harassing entrepreneurs and stifling dev=
elopment? In this, Berlin reflects Germany's broader electoral and economic=
 conundrum:
 how to reform when a growing majority of voters directly benefit from the =
old yet unsustainable order?

=20
    As most Berliners see it, Wowereit has done well merely by keeping thin=
gs from getting worse. And in time, it may well be that Berlin's poor-but-s=
exy cachet turns out to be an advantage. Tourist numbers are up 22 percent =
this year--driven, officials say, mainly by young Europeans coming to play =
in the city's ever-cool club scene. The dearth of other economic activity, =
and the accompanying lack of free-spending business travelers, means hotels=
 are dirt cheap. A room in a four- or five-star hotel (the only category fo=
r which comparative numbers are available) costs an average of =E2=82=AC127=
, versus =E2=82=AC277 in London and =E2=82=AC294 in Milan. As a result, Ber=
lin has outpaced Barcelona and Rome as a tourist destination and is now sec=
ond in Europe only to Paris and London. The city's raffish edge, in fact, i=
s part of its drawing power--not unlike Berlin in its Weimar heyday. Recent=
ly the official tourist board added an "adults only" section to its Web sit=
e, promoting, among other
 venues, the legendary Kit Kat, a techno club where "guests act out their s=
exual fantasies."

=20
    Unsurprisingly, creative industries like music, fashion and design are =
thriving in the new Berlin. They profit not only from low operating costs a=
nd cheap rents but also from a steady influx of artists and counterculture =
types arriving from elsewhere. Fashion designer Carolin Sinemus, whose Sisi=
 Wasabi brand turns out traditional German Trachten with a 21st-century twi=
st, says she knows of no other city where start-up costs are so ridiculousl=
y low. She's part of a burgeoning industry of more than 800 small, independ=
ent fashion labels, most of them only a few years old.

=20
    They've been joined, since 1998, by more than 300 new film and TV produ=
ction start-ups and an equal number of new music labels, according to Tanja=
 M=C3=BChlhans of Berlin's Economics Ministry. Tim Renner, CEO of record la=
bel Motor Music, says, "Berlin is like New York in the early 1980s--bankrup=
t but incredibly creative. Since it costs nothing, you can afford to make f=
ewer compromises and be more radical." That would include Super700, a band =
of three Albanian sisters his label has produced. Berlin's newest poster ch=
ild of sexy chic is Graft, an interior-design team that has raked in awards=
 for the futuristic organic shapes that grace the new Fix restaurant at the=
 Bellagio in Las Vegas, as well as Berlin's ultrastylish Hotel Q, recently =
voted the world's best designed hotel by Travel & Leisure magazine.
=20
=20
    The experimental has, of course, always been a hallmark of Berlin. Back=
 in '89--as a half-forgotten outpost of the cold war, surviving on subsidie=
s handed out to citizens and companies merely for staying--it was an oasis =
where artists, nonconformists and revolutionaries could rub elbows, secure =
in their tatterdemalion chic. Today, Berlin feels a bit the same way, this =
time removed from much of the rat race of globalization. Sure, the city has=
 huge, unsolved problems--from dysfunctional schools to hundreds of thousan=
ds of missing jobs. And now, as then, Berlin is hopelessly dependent on pay=
ments from Germany's richer regions, lavish flows that create very little i=
ncentive for Wowereit's government to cut costs or promote business growth =
and boost tax revenues. But as long as their city stays cheap, cool and liv=
able, most Berliners (and of course their visitors) don't seem to mind.=20



http://www.keepmedia.com/pubs/Newsweek/2006/09/18/1807748?ba=3Da&bi=3D16&bp=
=3D64

storage units.

On Sep 20, 2006, at 2:02 PM, <dangrsmind@yahoo.com> =20
<dangrsmind@yahoo.com> wrote:

> This story from Newsweek strikes a chord as we get ready to =20
> celebrate our little local version of the Love  Parade....
>
> Peter
>
>
>
> Berlin's coolest new club, Kubik, hides behind an unmarked gate =20
> across from a crumbling house full of squatters in a derelict =20
> downtown lot on the river Spree. It's built entirely from =20
> refashioned industrial containers emanating a translucent green =20
> light. If they seem to be almost alive, it's no accident; thanks to =20=

> an edgy software interface, they pulsate to DJ Bobby Fr=F6hlich's =20
> smooth post-techno beats. Amid the occasional sweet scent of =20
> cannabis, crowds of twentysomethings party until dawn. Sic transit =20
> Gloria Mundi . This weekend the cubes will be taken down and, poof, =20=

> Kubik will be no more.
>
>
>     Quirky, creative and outrageously cheap--the cover charge is =20
> but a single euro, and beers cost =802--Kubik is a perfect metaphor =20=

> for the new Berlin. Remember all that post-unification speculation =20
> that the city, as a rising Germany's new capital, would =20
> metamorphose from a gritty outpost of the cold war into yet another =20=

> homogenized, prosperous Eurotropolis? Forget it. The post-unity =20
> boom has fizzled--and most Berliners are perfectly happy about it.
>
>
>     Once again, their city is both Germany's undisputed lifestyle =20
> capital--and worst economic laggard. Judging by the bustling caf=E9s, =20=

> thriving art galleries and ubiquitous club scene (think Kubik, =20
> squared), you'd never know that Berlin suffers from nearly 20 =20
> percent unemployment. Per capita income is the lowest of any major =20
> German city. The economy has shrunk by 10 percent over the last =20
> decade, and the city's public debt, amounting to some =8080 billion, =20=

> is more than that of Peru, Ecuador and Guatemala combined. Kubik is =20=

> a symbol of all this, too. After all, the lot on which it stands, =20
> free of charge, has been on the market for nearly 15 years--prime =20
> downtown riverside real estate that can't find takers at one fifth =20
> what it would cost in London.
>
>
>     All this would be a cause of outrage in most world cities. Yet =20
> Berliners are at ease. Most were tickled when Klaus Wowereit, their =20=

> popular partygoing mayor, dubbed the town "poor but sexy" late last =20=

> year. A Social Democrat governing in coalition with the communists, =20=

> the openly gay 52-year-old is a shoo-in to win Berlin's Sept. 17 =20
> election. His opponent, a sober-suited conservative, gets zero =20
> traction. Why? Because Wowi, as he's called, has managed to finesse =20=

> the mess. Though nearly bankrupt, the city has kept budget cutbacks =20=

> small enough to avoid angering voters. That's important, given that =20=

> a whopping 41 percent of Berliners live off government subsidies--=20
> pensions, welfare, unemployment--and that the city's 200,000 civil =20
> servants make up one of the municipality's biggest voting blocs. =20
> And so what if that Kafkaesque bureaucracy is infamous for =20
> harassing entrepreneurs and stifling development? In this, Berlin =20
> reflects Germany's broader electoral and economic conundrum:
>  how to reform when a growing majority of voters directly benefit =20
> from the old yet unsustainable order?
>
>
>     As most Berliners see it, Wowereit has done well merely by =20
> keeping things from getting worse. And in time, it may well be that =20=

> Berlin's poor-but-sexy cachet turns out to be an advantage. Tourist =20=

> numbers are up 22 percent this year--driven, officials say, mainly =20
> by young Europeans coming to play in the city's ever-cool club =20
> scene. The dearth of other economic activity, and the accompanying =20
> lack of free-spending business travelers, means hotels are dirt =20
> cheap. A room in a four- or five-star hotel (the only category for =20
> which comparative numbers are available) costs an average of =80127, =20=

> versus =80277 in London and =80294 in Milan. As a result, Berlin has =20=

> outpaced Barcelona and Rome as a tourist destination and is now =20
> second in Europe only to Paris and London. The city's raffish edge, =20=

> in fact, is part of its drawing power--not unlike Berlin in its =20
> Weimar heyday. Recently the official tourist board added an "adults =20=

> only" section to its Web site, promoting, among other
>  venues, the legendary Kit Kat, a techno club where "guests act out =20=

> their sexual fantasies."
>
>
>     Unsurprisingly, creative industries like music, fashion and =20
> design are thriving in the new Berlin. They profit not only from =20
> low operating costs and cheap rents but also from a steady influx =20
> of artists and counterculture types arriving from elsewhere. =20
> Fashion designer Carolin Sinemus, whose Sisi Wasabi brand turns out =20=

> traditional German Trachten with a 21st-century twist, says she =20
> knows of no other city where start-up costs are so ridiculously =20
> low. She's part of a burgeoning industry of more than 800 small, =20
> independent fashion labels, most of them only a few years old.
>
>
>     They've been joined, since 1998, by more than 300 new film and =20
> TV production start-ups and an equal number of new music labels, =20
> according to Tanja M=FChlhans of Berlin's Economics Ministry. Tim =20
> Renner, CEO of record label Motor Music, says, "Berlin is like New =20
> York in the early 1980s--bankrupt but incredibly creative. Since it =20=

> costs nothing, you can afford to make fewer compromises and be more =20=

> radical." That would include Super700, a band of three Albanian =20
> sisters his label has produced. Berlin's newest poster child of =20
> sexy chic is Graft, an interior-design team that has raked in =20
> awards for the futuristic organic shapes that grace the new Fix =20
> restaurant at the Bellagio in Las Vegas, as well as Berlin's =20
> ultrastylish Hotel Q, recently voted the world's best designed =20
> hotel by Travel & Leisure magazine.
>
>
>     The experimental has, of course, always been a hallmark of =20
> Berlin. Back in '89--as a half-forgotten outpost of the cold war, =20
> surviving on subsidies handed out to citizens and companies merely =20
> for staying--it was an oasis where artists, nonconformists and =20
> revolutionaries could rub elbows, secure in their tatterdemalion =20
> chic. Today, Berlin feels a bit the same way, this time removed =20
> from much of the rat race of globalization. Sure, the city has =20
> huge, unsolved problems--from dysfunctional schools to hundreds of =20
> thousands of missing jobs. And now, as then, Berlin is hopelessly =20
> dependent on payments from Germany's richer regions, lavish flows =20
> that create very little incentive for Wowereit's government to cut =20
> costs or promote business growth and boost tax revenues. But as =20
> long as their city stays cheap, cool and livable, most Berliners =20
> (and of course their visitors) don't seem to mind.
>
>
>
> http://www.keepmedia.com/pubs/Newsweek/2006/09/18/1807748?=20
> ba=3Da&bi=3D16&bp=3D64
>
>

awesome idea.  there are lots of unused intermodal shipping =20
containers (seaboxes) sitting in and around oakland because of the =20
imbalance of trade with Asia.  it costs money to ship empty =20
containers back, so they just sit here, unused, or sold off as =20
storage units.

all we need is a patch of dirt, and we could set up an instant club. :-)

On Sep 20, 2006, at 2:02 PM, <dangrsmind@yahoo.com> =20
<dangrsmind@yahoo.com> wrote:

> This story from Newsweek strikes a chord as we get ready to =20
> celebrate our little local version of the Love  Parade....
>
> Peter
>
>
>
> Berlin's coolest new club, Kubik, hides behind an unmarked gate =20
> across from a crumbling house full of squatters in a derelict =20
> downtown lot on the river Spree. It's built entirely from =20
> refashioned industrial containers emanating a translucent green =20
> light. If they seem to be almost alive, it's no accident; thanks to =20
> an edgy software interface, they pulsate to DJ Bobby Fr=C3=B6hlich's =20
> smooth post-techno beats. Amid the occasional sweet scent of =20
> cannabis, crowds of twentysomethings party until dawn. Sic transit =20
> Gloria Mundi . This weekend the cubes will be taken down and, poof, =20
> Kubik will be no more.
>
>
>     Quirky, creative and outrageously cheap--the cover charge is =20
> but a single euro, and beers cost =E2=82=AC2--Kubik is a perfect metaphor=
 =20
> for the new Berlin. Remember all that post-unification speculation =20
> that the city, as a rising Germany's new capital, would =20
> metamorphose from a gritty outpost of the cold war into yet another =20
> homogenized, prosperous Eurotropolis? Forget it. The post-unity =20
> boom has fizzled--and most Berliners are perfectly happy about it.
>
>
>     Once again, their city is both Germany's undisputed lifestyle =20
> capital--and worst economic laggard. Judging by the bustling caf=C3=A9s, =
=20
> thriving art galleries and ubiquitous club scene (think Kubik, =20
> squared), you'd never know that Berlin suffers from nearly 20 =20
> percent unemployment. Per capita income is the lowest of any major =20
> German city. The economy has shrunk by 10 percent over the last =20
> decade, and the city's public debt, amounting to some =E2=82=AC80 billion=
, =20
> is more than that of Peru, Ecuador and Guatemala combined. Kubik is =20
> a symbol of all this, too. After all, the lot on which it stands, =20
> free of charge, has been on the market for nearly 15 years--prime =20
> downtown riverside real estate that can't find takers at one fifth =20
> what it would cost in London.
>
>
>     All this would be a cause of outrage in most world cities. Yet =20
> Berliners are at ease. Most were tickled when Klaus Wowereit, their =20
> popular partygoing mayor, dubbed the town "poor but sexy" late last =20
> year. A Social Democrat governing in coalition with the communists, =20
> the openly gay 52-year-old is a shoo-in to win Berlin's Sept. 17 =20
> election. His opponent, a sober-suited conservative, gets zero =20
> traction. Why? Because Wowi, as he's called, has managed to finesse =20
> the mess. Though nearly bankrupt, the city has kept budget cutbacks =20
> small enough to avoid angering voters. That's important, given that =20
> a whopping 41 percent of Berliners live off government subsidies--=20
> pensions, welfare, unemployment--and that the city's 200,000 civil =20
> servants make up one of the municipality's biggest voting blocs. =20
> And so what if that Kafkaesque bureaucracy is infamous for =20
> harassing entrepreneurs and stifling development? In this, Berlin =20
> reflects Germany's broader electoral and economic conundrum:
>  how to reform when a growing majority of voters directly benefit =20
> from the old yet unsustainable order?
>
>
>     As most Berliners see it, Wowereit has done well merely by =20
> keeping things from getting worse. And in time, it may well be that =20
> Berlin's poor-but-sexy cachet turns out to be an advantage. Tourist =20
> numbers are up 22 percent this year--driven, officials say, mainly =20
> by young Europeans coming to play in the city's ever-cool club =20
> scene. The dearth of other economic activity, and the accompanying =20
> lack of free-spending business travelers, means hotels are dirt =20
> cheap. A room in a four- or five-star hotel (the only category for =20
> which comparative numbers are available) costs an average of =E2=82=AC127=
, =20
> versus =E2=82=AC277 in London and =E2=82=AC294 in Milan. As a result, Ber=
lin has =20
> outpaced Barcelona and Rome as a tourist destination and is now =20
> second in Europe only to Paris and London. The city's raffish edge, =20
> in fact, is part of its drawing power--not unlike Berlin in its =20
> Weimar heyday. Recently the official tourist board added an "adults =20
> only" section to its Web site, promoting, among other
>  venues, the legendary Kit Kat, a techno club where "guests act out =20
> their sexual fantasies."
>
>
>     Unsurprisingly, creative industries like music, fashion and =20
> design are thriving in the new Berlin. They profit not only from =20
> low operating costs and cheap rents but also from a steady influx =20
> of artists and counterculture types arriving from elsewhere. =20
> Fashion designer Carolin Sinemus, whose Sisi Wasabi brand turns out =20
> traditional German Trachten with a 21st-century twist, says she =20
> knows of no other city where start-up costs are so ridiculously =20
> low. She's part of a burgeoning industry of more than 800 small, =20
> independent fashion labels, most of them only a few years old.
>
>
>     They've been joined, since 1998, by more than 300 new film and =20
> TV production start-ups and an equal number of new music labels, =20
> according to Tanja M=C3=BChlhans of Berlin's Economics Ministry. Tim =20
> Renner, CEO of record label Motor Music, says, "Berlin is like New =20
> York in the early 1980s--bankrupt but incredibly creative. Since it =20
> costs nothing, you can afford to make fewer compromises and be more =20
> radical." That would include Super700, a band of three Albanian =20
> sisters his label has produced. Berlin's newest poster child of =20
> sexy chic is Graft, an interior-design team that has raked in =20
> awards for the futuristic organic shapes that grace the new Fix =20
> restaurant at the Bellagio in Las Vegas, as well as Berlin's =20
> ultrastylish Hotel Q, recently voted the world's best designed =20
> hotel by Travel & Leisure magazine.
>
>
>     The experimental has, of course, always been a hallmark of =20
> Berlin. Back in '89--as a half-forgotten outpost of the cold war, =20
> surviving on subsidies handed out to citizens and companies merely =20
> for staying--it was an oasis where artists, nonconformists and =20
> revolutionaries could rub elbows, secure in their tatterdemalion =20
> chic. Today, Berlin feels a bit the same way, this time removed =20
> from much of the rat race of globalization. Sure, the city has =20
> huge, unsolved problems--from dysfunctional schools to hundreds of =20
> thousands of missing jobs. And now, as then, Berlin is hopelessly =20
> dependent on payments from Germany's richer regions, lavish flows =20
> that create very little incentive for Wowereit's government to cut =20
> costs or promote business growth and boost tax revenues. But as =20
> long as their city stays cheap, cool and livable, most Berliners =20
> (and of course their visitors) don't seem to mind.
>
>
>

Symbiosis Gathering 2006
Angels Camp, CA . 21-25 September 2006
www.SymbiosisGathering.com

The intention of Symbiosis is to create a gathering space for people to=20
exchange ideas, express creativity, explore spirituality, camp together, =
and=20
enjoy themselves in a positive and nurturing environment. We seek to =
align=20
ourselves for positive change through the creative arts, music, holistic =

medicine, and communal networking. Join us for a variety of workshops, =
guest=20
speakers, and activities to enrich your life in addition to a =
full-strength=20
international music bill.

This year's lineup is broader, larger, and live-er than last year, with =
the=20
hopes of bringing even more cutting edge talent together for a unified=20
gathering of underground music styles.

Subject: Re: [sfraves] shooting in the sunset

It seems things are heating up here in San Francisco...

I'm not exactly sure what happened here in the Sunset yet, and the police aren't saying.  It appears to be an attempted robbery, and the guy that was being robbed took a swing at the robber who then shot him in the shoulder.  There's blood on a lampost and the sidewalk and I saw an ambulance take the guy away.  I'm pretty sure he was alive.  The police were right there and chased the shooter up my street. I saw that part too.  

Police combed the neighbor for a couple of hours in the dark looking for the weapon but didn't find it.  Not sure if they caught the shooter or not.

With all the parties this weekend and the parade people should be extra careful. Last year there was a very high police presence at the festival grounds, kind of over the top IMO, and I know at least one person that's not going this year bc of that.  But we should all be extra careful around the afterparties and look out for each other.  Sometimes these sorts of events attract people with bad intentions in addition to the usual happy sparkley people.  Keep alert if you are party hopping in the SOMA area especially.

Peace,

Peter

Just a guess here, but does it stand for Massive Multiplayer Online?

BTW I can't stand WOW and Everquest. Not because it sucks, but because I've
seen too many friends get addicted to it and wind up wasting away on it.
Sorta like how people these days are Myspace addicts. I had a friend in
college that ended up dropping out because he would just sit in front of the
computer all day and night long. No showers, no studys, no class, just
warcrack. Guess that's what happens to spoiled kids that have their parents
pay their way through college.

Maybe they need to listen to breathe by Pink Floyd.

Good Dad!

I've been trying to teach my oldest Alex (almost 15!) to program and its been an uphill battle. I should have started him earlier.  Now with my younger two, we are off to the right start.  I'm teaching Bennett (3 1/2) about probability theory, and I just bought him some giant dice.  He likes to roll them and add up the dots.  Next: no limit hold-em.  Papa needs a new pair of Pumas!

Anyway, Alex is  more interested in the narrative/storytelling aspects of gaming.  He's recently been using some off the shelf tools to build his own Warcraft-like game and just joined the creative writing club at school so I'm encouraging that angle.  

Peace,

Peter

COME-UNITY: 15 YEAR BIRTHDAY PARTY!!!!

ON FRIDAY SEPTEMBER 29TH 

Malachy and company have put together an extraordinary evening of music for
this special occasion, and I'm certain it will be one of the most memorable
parties of the year...

IN THE MAIN ROOM:

SPECIAL GUEST GREEN VELVET (Relief Recordings, Chicago)

GARTH
JENO
SIMON
LITTLE JOHN


IN THE RED ROOM:

FABRICIO PACENHA  (Hypno DJs/Brazil)
tag team with DJ ADNAN

T.K. DISCO


IN THE LOFT ROOM

DJ PLATURN
COLOSSUS
ADONIS
DAVID GOLD
DISTANT RELATIVES 'live'


We will be using a separate entrance with mostly our own door people. 

1015 Folsom  @ 6th
10 pm-6am  21+  $20 door  $15 presale  $10 by 11pm  SFSMC passholders honored
Presale tix at:  www.wantickets.com, Tweekin Records (SF), Solid Grooves (SJ)

On Fri, 22 Sep 2006, J.C. wrote:
-&e->And the unpaid labels list is here:

BWAAAAAHAHAHAHAHAHAHAHAHAHA.  Their site is imploded and taking forever.  
Some of us are used to this though...

WARNING-SHIT TALKING RANT BELOW

Maybe Chris Jackson can finally recover some of his well deserved scrilla.

No joke, he once called me flipping out from a drive thru on his cell 
phone, as Live105 was using one of his tracks without permission in the 
background of a public service announcement.

You see, Chris Jackson puts his pants on one leg at a time, just like 
everybody else.  Except when he does, he makes really good records that go 
unnoticed in his own home town but are cherished collectors items 
elsewhere and licensed all over the place.  How the fuck did the hoover 
thieves and trance drones get so much credit here for doing nothing while 
we let a whole homegrown subgenre go by?

Someday, perhaps history will realize it forgot to mention a wicked 
community of productivity, creativity and progress we'll call the South 
Bay techno & house scene bound by of love of progress in music, 
ridiculously irie doja and Newcastle.  Or, nothing will change and we'll 
just know we were badass.

Either way... wouldn't change our reasons for having done it in the first 
place, just a shame.
andyw aka mutor aka that bitter bitch who goes off from time to time on 
sfr who has little to hold back his fury except a check for a track on the 
next release of DDR hahaha

For those who don't yet know, this is the sound of sick soulful tech funk 
from the kids down south...
http://dobox.dajis.net/site/?page_id=3   <- the real san jo deal

andyw - mutorsoundsystem - saturn5.com/andy

ement without paying you, you can and should sue them.  I managed IP and li=
censing at another former employer (MetaTools) and IMO there is no excuse f=
or using unlicensed musical or visual works in an advertisement.  No excuse=
.  Humorously MetaTools (then MetaCreations) was sued by the lead singer of=
 the Cramps for using his image in a advertisement after I left. FWIW.=0A=

That would be Live105 [KITS]..105.3 FM...not Live365.  I actually had to let
Live105 know that I would be contacting my attorney if they didn't pull the
ad...which if I recall correctly was a Sony Playstation2 spot....I nearly
crashed my car!  Apparently they got a copy of my mix album from somewhere.
They actually had the nerve to say that they would trade me the song used on
the spot for "airplay" on that horrible underground music show they air on
the weekend.  I think Mars and Mystre were involved with the show.  Needless
to say...I passed!  LOL!

A life long buddy of mine used to work at Live365...Steve Musgrave.  Did you
know him Peter??  He's a programmer, so I would imagine if you were the CTO
he might have worked for you.

-----Original Message-----
From: dangrsmind@yahoo.com [mailto:dangrsmind@yahoo.com] 
Sent: Friday, September 22, 2006 1:40 PM
To: AndyW; Chris Jackson
Cc: sfraves@hyperreal.org
Subject: Re: [sfraves] a note to the producers

Well, as a former Live365 employee, let me first apologize for whomever was
lame enough to use Chris' track without permission.  I'd be curious to know
when that happened.  

I was the CTO at the founding of the company and was there from 1998-2001.
If someone is using your track in an advertisement without paying you, you
can and should sue them.  I managed IP and licensing at another former
employer (MetaTools) and IMO there is no excuse for using unlicensed musical
or visual works in an advertisement.  No excuse.  Humorously MetaTools (then
MetaCreations) was sued by the lead singer of the Cramps for using his image
in a advertisement after I left. FWIW.

I also can tell you that Live365 spent a lot of money implementing the
accounting system to provide SoundExchange with the data they required to
enable payment to artists like Chris, so I sincerely hope he does get some
"scrilla" out of it.  Their claims that they "can't find" any of these
artists or labels are ridiculous.  Maybe they can't spell "Google"...

FWIW I never listen to Live365, the service has significantly diverged from
my original goals and objectives for it, and furthermore has completely
failed to evolve with the times.  I have some stories to tell about all of
that, but it will require a lot of alcohol to get me talking.

Peace,

Peter

WARNING-SHIT TALKING RANT BELOW

Maybe Chris Jackson can finally recover some of his well deserved scrilla.

No joke, he once called me flipping out from a drive thru on his cell 
phone, as Live105 was using one of his tracks without permission in the 
background of a public service announcement.

You see, Chris Jackson puts his pants on one leg at a time, just like 
everybody else.  Except when he does, he makes really good records that go 
unnoticed in his own home town but are cherished collectors items 
elsewhere and licensed all over the place.  How the fuck did the hoover 
thieves and trance drones get so much credit here for doing nothing while 
we let a whole homegrown subgenre go by?

Someday, perhaps history will realize it forgot to mention a wicked 
community of productivity, creativity and progress we'll call the South 
Bay techno & house scene bound by of love of progress in music, 
ridiculously irie doja and Newcastle.  Or, nothing will change and we'll 
just know we were badass.

Either way... wouldn't change our reasons for having done it in the first 
place, just a shame.

A similar thing happened to me Chris, although less severe, I found out by a
fan contacting me that my mix (tussinspace#1) was played on some Korean
terrestrial radio station. They never contacted me or gave credit or
anything. Not that I would want money, but recognition would have been nice.
A lot of the songs in that mix were edits or mixes done by me and it also
included one of my tracks. I couldn't figure out the station name because it
was all in Korean. Oh well. Your situation is a lot worse, if my song was
used for a commercial I would go ape shit and contact an attorney.
