>Well, as a former Live365 employee, let me first apologize for whomever was
>lame enough to use Chris' track without permission.  I'd be curious to know
>when that happened.
>
>I was the CTO at the founding of the company and was there from 1998-2001.
>If someone is using your track in an advertisement without paying you, you
>can and should sue them.  I managed IP and licensing at another former
>employer (MetaTools) and IMO there is no excuse for using unlicensed musical
>or visual works in an advertisement.  No excuse.  Humorously MetaTools (then
>MetaCreations) was sued by the lead singer of the Cramps for using his image
>in a advertisement after I left. FWIW.

>accounting system to provide SoundExchange with the data they required to

i was going to restart the quote of the day on september 11, the five  
year anniversary.  i just didn't feel up to it that day, but these  
thoughts have been burning a hole in my mind and they must be heard  
in this forum, here and now.  so here goes.

i'm surprised of the lack of discussion of 9/11 on the list when the  
evidence is overwhelmingly mounting that it was an inside job by  
criminal elements in our own government.  now maybe i missed a  
thread.  or maybe you're just discussing this amongst yourselves.  i  
really hope so.  no, but honestly.  don't be afraid to have a  
discussion about it right here.  last i heard this was an open  
forum.  and we shouldn't be afraid to express our opinions about this  
subject.  in fact, i think we have to.

i didn't want to believe 9/11 being an inside job could be true at  
first, but if it is true, if more people don't start speaking up  
about it and burning a copy of one of the many DVD's out there on the  
internet and giving them to friends, i fear we could be headed for  
world war 3, all started by more staged terror attacks.

anyway, those are my 2 cents, unsolicited, yes, but i think it's  
important more people start talking about this instead of just trying  
to forget about it and hope it will all just go away.  sorry, didn't  
mean to ruin the mood from the lovefest threads.

have a nice day.  fog out

9/11 - I have never said anything on the topic but since you put it out 
there..

How to build a new social democracy

America has overextended itself, attempting to democratize the world in the 
name of raising our own standard of living through market expansion and 
imperialism.  I believe we got what was coming to us and that message was 
clear.  Butt out of regions that don't want your demoralizing ways.. 
however fundamental or extremist those moral or ethical views of life are.

I believe we should pull out of the east, divert all war monies to 
alternative energy development, release oil from out strategic national 
development policy, and promote fair market exchange, and fair labor 
practices around the world.  I think we should cut imports and enact tariffs 
on all non-hybrid or alternative fuel vehicles.

Repeal all patriot act legislation.  Repeal all wiretapping legislation.  
Decommission the Homeland Security Administration.  Remove the provisions 
for executive powers act in non-war faring times.  Uphold Geneva conventions 
in all military prisons and tribunals.  On a side note: leave the CIA budget 
and powers intact - don't ask me why.. but I think we still need some teeth 
and information to manage our new isolationism.

Perhaps if our prerogatives for global social responsibility were as 
sensitive to the needs of the world as our European allies, we wouldnt be 
the *direct* targets of terrorism.  Do you think our standard of living, our 
education, and our retirement packages are better than anyone in France or 
Italy, or Germany, or Spain?  I would hasten to say that although I am a 
patriotic American in many respects, I struggle with out global intentions 
and feel military insurgence is not the way to manage our economic needs.  
Oil is not worth ripping apart the social fabric of the world.  It is IMHO 
the terror the breeds all the injustice we see and easy target for us to 
deal with by removing it from the lexicon of social development.




SFR: Ranger
San Francisco
plurranger@hotmail.com
Who knows where the night leads
It's dark and no one can see





From: Deepfog <sfgroove@deepfog.com>
To: "The Twilight Laser Outpost (West)" <sfraves@hyperreal.org>
Subject: [sfraves] (nrr) QOD (Mon)
Date: Mon, 25 Sep 2006 06:09:04 -0400

i was going to restart the quote of the day on september 11, the five  year 
anniversary.  i just didn't feel up to it that day, but these  thoughts have 
been burning a hole in my mind and they must be heard  in this forum, here 
and now.  so here goes.

i'm surprised of the lack of discussion of 9/11 on the list when the  
evidence is overwhelmingly mounting that it was an inside job by  criminal 
elements in our own government.  now maybe i missed a  thread.  or maybe 
you're just discussing this amongst yourselves.  i  really hope so.  no, but 
honestly.  don't be afraid to have a  discussion about it right here.  last 
i heard this was an open  forum.  and we shouldn't be afraid to express our 
opinions about this  subject.  in fact, i think we have to.

i didn't want to believe 9/11 being an inside job could be true at  first, 
but if it is true, if more people don't start speaking up  about it and 
burning a copy of one of the many DVD's out there on the  internet and 
giving them to friends, i fear we could be headed for  world war 3, all 
started by more staged terror attacks.

anyway, those are my 2 cents, unsolicited, yes, but i think it's  important 
more people start talking about this instead of just trying  to forget about 
it and hope it will all just go away.  sorry, didn't  mean to ruin the mood 
from the lovefest threads.

have a nice day.  fog out

--

We live in complete illegality.  As soon as somebody starts focusing  on 
some group or other for being 'illegal', i have to remind you that  this 
whole system is one continuous creeping coup; one insurrection  against law 
and constitution from beginning to end.

- Webster Griffin Tarpley

 about visiting the rabbit hole at Oxford where Alice actually fell in.=0A=

sation in the bathroom waiting for a stall about parenting with the guy tha=
t had recently gotten married.  Dude don't worry, you are thinking about al=
l the right things.=0A=0AThe lesbians that kept wanting to stroke my, err, =
flamingo...=0A=0AI had two random encounters with Agent Smith.  But he was =
on a secret mission apparently.=0A=0AMy wife's idea for the "flamingo bong"=
 which spawned several other fabulous flamingo fashion and technology ideas=
.=0A=0AWe went over to the Opel room for Rennie Pilgrem's set...ok well it =
was like weird. Too slow or something, so we went back to Evil Breaks for m=
ore flamingo love and rocking beats.  And per Marc(o) he does have a large =
head, but it was fairly symmetric as far as I could tell.=0A=0AThe music in=
 the Evil Breaks room just rocked the whole night long IMO. Carbon Communit=
y and General Midi were great.  The Opel room was up and down.  I was sort =
of surprised how few people were in the Tantra room most of the time.=0A=0A=

l area was really good.  And it was cool to be outside.  Umm, but what was =
with that weird sailor-esque whistling track?  I thought I was on Gilligan'=
s island for a minute there.  I didn't see Mary Anne or Ginger unfortunatel=
y.  Anyway, one of the best chill vibes I've seen recently, but I couldn't =
get a seat on the bean bags!=0A=0AWe cruised over to the Opel room again fo=
r Hyper's set which was good, but the female DJ that came on after him was =
even better...she rocked it. Not sure who she was tho...=0A=0AThen we had t=
o leave.  It seemed like the party was getting shut down as we walked out t=
he front door...=0A=0AApologies if I left you out.  Brain cells not working=
 too good today.=0A=0AOnly negative: goonish security dudes giving me the e=

ingo!=0A=0AIn sum, my faith in the SF party scene is rejuvenated and re-ene=

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Love Infusion -- Party Review

--0-1137268227-1159218074=:20351
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=iso-8859-1
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

great post. i agree on many counts. so you're the dude with the flamingo, huh? i totally saw you at the party but we never met. you looked very festive :)

this party definitely had a vibe that i haven't been able to find lately. 4 areas of kickass music and a ton of smiling faces... i met a lot of people (including bam from this list) and they were all super cool. after all was said and done, i was feeling pretty damn good about the state of parties here. it was especially inspiring to see 4 different crews come together so well. i referred to this event as "the voltron of afterparties" on another board, and i'm happy to see it lived up to my lofty expectations.

thanks for the kind words about the ambient mafia space. my opinion is admittedly very biased, but i believe it was a great addition to the party as well. i thought i was the queen of weird tracks in that area, but the whistling sailor tune was not mine so i may have to give up my throne ;)

i was front and center for carbon community and i thought that was some great music. i was a little bummed that the drummer wasn't there as well, but that's just because i like excuses to see my friends. great set though - perfect combination of hard and melodic. the visuals at that time were also stellar.

i think the dj who played after hyper in the opel room was melyss (of Sister) and i agree that she was bangin' it out in there! i caught part of hyper and was really into the funky records he was playing, but i also though melyss kinda showed him up on a technical level.

one of my favorite things about this party was that i had room to dance. there were a lot of people there for sure, but it wasn't sardine-style in the rooms. if i wanted to dance big, i could... and at certain points, i did. it was awesome.

thanks to everyone who made this one possible! this year was the most fun i've had at any of the love parade/fest soirees.

love,
mo

dangrsmind@yahoo.com wrote: Great party.  Great people.  Great music.   I met a lot of people, I'm sorry I can't remember all of you right at the moment!

Some highlights:

The tall thin girl that was dancing in the evil breaks room!  Wow!  She was one of the best dancers I've ever seen.

The visuals in the Evil Breaks room were consistently amazing.

Flamingo shadow games...

Adrianna and Keith were like toasty marshmallows.  Good to see you guys tho!

Hugs from Osby...the second best hug of the night!  The other one was from my wife ;)

Mary Ellen was a sweetie...

The guy that told us about visiting the rabbit hole at Oxford where Alice actually fell in.

The nice couple we were dancing with in the Opel room!  

The conversation in the bathroom waiting for a stall about parenting with the guy that had recently gotten married.  Dude don't worry, you are thinking about all the right things.

The lesbians that kept wanting to stroke my, err, flamingo...

I had two random encounters with Agent Smith.  But he was on a secret mission apparently.

My wife's idea for the "flamingo bong" which spawned several other fabulous flamingo fashion and technology ideas.

We went over to the Opel room for Rennie Pilgrem's set...ok well it was like weird. Too slow or something, so we went back to Evil Breaks for more flamingo love and rocking beats.  And per Marc(o) he does have a large head, but it was fairly symmetric as far as I could tell.

The music in the Evil Breaks room just rocked the whole night long IMO. Carbon Community and General Midi were great.  The Opel room was up and down.  I was sort of surprised how few people were in the Tantra room most of the time.

I was really glad the Ambient Mafia got added to the party because the chill area was really good.  And it was cool to be outside.  Umm, but what was with that weird sailor-esque whistling track?  I thought I was on Gilligan's island for a minute there.  I didn't see Mary Anne or Ginger unfortunately.  Anyway, one of the best chill vibes I've seen recently, but I couldn't get a seat on the bean bags!

We cruised over to the Opel room again for Hyper's set which was good, but the female DJ that came on after him was even better...she rocked it. Not sure who she was tho...

Then we had to leave.  It seemed like the party was getting shut down as we walked out the front door...

Apologies if I left you out.  Brain cells not working too good today.

Only negative: goonish security dudes giving me the evil eye.  Big ups to the one security guy that asked me if I got tired of carrying my flamingo.  However dumb question!  It was a fluffy light up flamingo!

In sum, my faith in the SF party scene is rejuvenated and re-energized.  Thanks to Evil Breaks, Opel, Tantra, and Ambient Mafia, Viberation, and anyone else I've forgotten.  See y'all next time.

Peace,

Peter

one of my burning man campmates is really involved in the hawaiian scene out there, and it's my understanding that it's a lot of psy. the main parties i know of out there are the Hawaii Electronic Music Festival (HEMF) which i think is in Hilo and normally in january? if memory serves, the website is www.bigislandlove.com

there is a crew out there that throws other parties as well, their name is ka pilina, but i can't remember the name of the last party offhand. check out their website too, which should be www.kapilina.org

you can look up a lot of the hawaiian events on tribe as well, i think all of those kids are fairly active on that site. 

love,
mo

if folsom street fair is your thing, that's cool, but personally i don't even bother. if you've seen 300 leather daddies in skimpy ballsack pouches, you've seen 'em all. i find it interesting for about half an hour and then i start to feel like i'm stuck in some weird time looped dungeon-world. i skipped it altogether this year. was it really that different? if so, i may have to rethink my strategy for 2007.

>From Jeno: 

Keep on Reachin'.. 

Join me this week folks for a special pre-Come Unity Anniversary show, which likely means I'll be digging out a few oldies and goldies for y'all. Wow, it's been 15 years already, who would have imagined we'd make it this far..!

And to compliment this week's celebration I'll have special guest dj Carlos on the show. In case you're not familiar with him - he helped define the rave scene here in the Bay Area in the mid-nineties with his natural hi-energy and boundless enthusiasm. After a hiatus of several years he has risen like the phoenix from the ashes and returned to his passion - djing. He is currently spinning again around the Bay Area, including his own monthly event "Pangea" at The Oasis in Oakland..

Noise from the Void with dj Carlos
Tuesday September 26th 9PM to ?
www.90hz.org



<http://www.asambleapopulardeoaxaca.com/>http://www.asambleapopulardeoaxaca.com/ 

MySpace:  http://www.myspace.com/DJApollo 

Tribenet:   <http://people.tribe.net/djapollo2k>http://people.tribe.net/djapollo2k 
                
House Music 101:  http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm

"Americans like to talk about (or be told about) Democracy but, when put to the test, usually find it to be an 'inconvenience.' We have opted instead for an authoritarian system disguised as a Democracy. We pay through the nose for an enormous joke-of-a-government, let it push us around, and then wonder how all those assholes got in there." - Frank Zappa 

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of the rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will gradually become visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

>

> tho!

> actually fell in.
>
> The nice couple we were dancing with in the Opel room!
>

> the guy that had recently gotten married.  Dude don't worry, you are
> thinking about all the right things.
>

>

> mission apparently.
>
> My wife's idea for the "flamingo bong" which spawned several other
> fabulous flamingo fashion and technology ideas.
>
> We went over to the Opel room for Rennie Pilgrem's set...ok well it was
> like weird. Too slow or something, so we went back to Evil Breaks for more
> flamingo love and rocking beats.  And per Marc(o) he does have a large
> head, but it was fairly symmetric as far as I could tell.
>
> The music in the Evil Breaks room just rocked the whole night long IMO.
> Carbon Community and General Midi were great.  The Opel room was up and
> down.  I was sort of surprised how few people were in the Tantra room most
> of the time.
>
> I was really glad the Ambient Mafia got added to the party because the
> chill area was really good.  And it was cool to be outside.  Umm, but what
> was with that weird sailor-esque whistling track?  I thought I was on
> Gilligan's island for a minute there.  I didn't see Mary Anne or Ginger
> unfortunately.  Anyway, one of the best chill vibes I've seen recently,
> but I couldn't get a seat on the bean bags!
>
> We cruised over to the Opel room again for Hyper's set which was good, but
> the female DJ that came on after him was even better...she rocked it. Not
> sure who she was tho...
>
> Then we had to leave.  It seemed like the party was getting shut down as
> we walked out the front door...
>
> Apologies if I left you out.  Brain cells not working too good today.
>
> Only negative: goonish security dudes giving me the evil eye.  Big ups to
> the one security guy that asked me if I got tired of carrying my flamingo.
>  However dumb question!  It was a fluffy light up flamingo!
>
> In sum, my faith in the SF party scene is rejuvenated and re-energized.

> anyone else I've forgotten.  See y'all next time.

Subject: [sfraves] Summer Music Conference & the new :code tv

So summer music conference starts tomorrow... the conference will
basically consist of like all these workshops & like info ummmm...
meetings about technology in music, law in the music bus, & so forth...
lol... the cool thing about SMC is that this weekend alone, they'll be
over 45 + events happening in honor of & because of SMC.. LoL... there's
gonna be4 heeeeeeeella DJs from all over the world.. la la la

get the 411 @ their home site:

http://sfsmc.com/index.php?option=com_frontpage&Itemid=1

I know i should brought this like up earlier so y'all coulda made your
plans to go to htis being that it kicks off tomorrow, but I just got this
ummm... ok... so check it... :code TV has been around now for the past
several years documenting like the haps in the SF Late NIght scene & local
artists... I've been working w/ Bruce, the Executive Producer & I guess
I'm like co-executive producer now, but yeah.... other than how :code used
to just like well... it was just a magazine show that aired on cable &
that was SF Local Cable....

But like now, :code will be spliting up into 2 shows:  :code TV & :code TV
News.. (seriously.. don't ask me what the difference is, that's Bruce's
idea & like i'm still tryin' to figure out where the "news" part comes
in....  Hello 2Day.. LoL.. But yeah.. we just wrapped our "pilot" episode
of :code TV News & here it is :)

this is a preview of the pilot episode
http://www.veoh.com/videoDetails.html?v=e1230764BQgmMNZ

in order to view the whole episode, you will need to download a veho
player...

But yeah... not to give away why these two go hand in hand, SMC & :code,
but after you watch the pilot... you'll see :)  LoL.. I actually will be
out and about during SMC gon' to some of them workshops :)  LoL

But yeah.. I'll make a full BSP on :code tv soon .... Please PLease
PLeasxe watch this pilot & gimme your opinoins Please... I know there some
like welll... things we gotta fix up already & I knmow that i talk to fast
& I"m kinda blah when in the studio.. lol...

But please.. let me know what u think :)  Thanks :)

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Summer Music Conference & the new :code tv

Osby this i great!  You have found your calling I think.  That video clip e=
nded sort of abruptly tho...=0A=0ANow on to the politics of dancing...=0A=
=0AAt the highest level SMC is an attempt to bring a world class dance musi=
c event similar to Miami's Winter Music Conference to SF.  Without some sor=
t of focal event lie this,many of these DJs would never even make it to SF =
at all.  FWIW I spoke at both the 2000 and 2001 WMCs on the future of elect=
ronic music and the Internet and I had an amazing time in Miami.=0A=0AAnywa=
y, with 20-20 hindsight, I now have some mixed feelings about WMC, and ther=
efore SMC too, because of the overwhelming influence of corporate sponsors =
and sponsorship dollars on these events.  =0A=0AFull disclosure: I was righ=
t in there as CTO of Live365.com trying to leverage our brand into WMC.  We=
 gave away a bunch of t-shirts and other crap, got banners etc. at the Ultr=
a Festival, sponsored a boat party with Essential Records and so forth.  It=
 was cool to do WMC on "other people's money"  but I now have some serious =
doubts about the impacts of commercialism and corporations on the dance mus=
ic scene.  =0A=0ADr. Motte's critiques of the 2006 Love Parade in Berlin se=
em relevant here.  That event has essentially been taken over by the corpor=
ate sponsors, who are primarily producers of alcoholic beverages as I under=
stand it.  (http://travel2.nytimes.com/2006/07/15/arts/music/15para.html?pa=
gewanted=3Dall and http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Love_Parade#Future_of_Love_=
Parade)  For the first time this year all of the floats in the parade were =
identical, just with different music and logos glued on the sides.=0A=0AI'm=
 concerned that SMC wll suck the vibe out of our little Lovefest and replac=
e it with a homogeous, logo plastered, frat party.  After this past weekend=
's glimmer of hope, I'd really hate to see that happen.  It seems that we'r=
e just emerging from the post dot.bomb, post 9/11, post over hyped "electro=
nica" binge that left the rave scene badly damaged.  Anyone else know what =
I mean?  AM I talking shit here?=0A=0AI don't want to get into the tired ol=
d beef that you can't be in it for the love if you are also in it to make m=
oney.  Hell I'd quit my job in instant if I thought I could support my fami=
ly somehow from the music scene.   But I'm talking about something more, th=
e subtle or not so subtle infiltration of every aspect of our lives by corp=
orations and brands.  Its the vibe killer.=0A=0AI solicit comments from the=
 peanut gallery,and I wonder if SMC is open enough to allow discussion of t=
his issue one one of its panels. =0A=0ARegards,=0A=0APeter=0A=0A=0A=0A=0A--=

lass dance music event similar to Miami's Winter Music Conference to SF.  W=
ithout some sort of focal event lie this,many of these DJs would never even=
 make it to SF at all.  FWIW I spoke at both the 2000 and 2001 WMCs on the =
future of electronic music and the Internet and I had an amazing time in Mi=
ami.=0A=0AAnyway, with 20-20 hindsight, I now have some mixed feelings abou=
t WMC, and therefore SMC too, because of the overwhelming influence of corp=

ure: I was right in there as CTO of Live365.com trying to leverage our bran=
d into WMC.  We gave away a bunch of t-shirts and other crap, got banners e=
tc. at the Ultra Festival, sponsored a boat party with Essential Records an=
d so forth.  It was cool to do WMC on "other people's money"  but I now hav=
e some serious doubts about the impacts of commercialism and corporations o=
n the dance music scene.  =0A=0ADr. Motte's critiques of the 2006 Love Para=
de in Berlin seem relevant here.  That event has essentially been taken ove=
r by the corporate sponsors, who are primarily producers of alcoholic bever=
ages as I understand it.  (http://travel2.nytimes.com/2006/07/15/arts/music=
/15para.html?pagewanted=3Dall and http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Love_Parade#=
Future_of_Love_Parade)  For the first time this year all of the floats in t=
he parade were identical, just with different music and logos glued on the =
sides.=0A=0AI'm concerned that SMC wll suck the vibe out of our little Love=
fest and replace it with a homogeous, logo plastered, frat party.  After th=
is past weekend's glimmer of hope, I'd really hate to see that happen.  It =
seems that we're just emerging from the post dot.bomb, post 9/11, post over=
 hyped "electronica" binge that left the rave scene badly damaged.  Anyone =
else know what I mean?  AM I talking shit here?=0A=0AI don't want to get in=
to the tired old beef that you can't be in it for the love if you are also =
in it to make money.  Hell I'd quit my job in instant if I thought I could =
support my family somehow from the music scene.   But I'm talking about som=
ething more, the subtle or not so subtle infiltration of every aspect of ou=
r lives by corporations and brands.  Its the vibe killer.=0A=0AI solicit co=
mments from the peanut gallery,and I wonder if SMC is open enough to allow =
discussion of this issue one one of its panels. =0A=0ARegards,=0A=0APeter=

eople in there dancing.  =0A=0AOne of the best parties I went to was hosted=

>There are a lot of events at WMC and not all of them are like that.  In my 
>experience. There were about 200 parties in 6 days last time I was there.
>
>I was there and I wasn't there to be "seen".  I did look however ;)  I 
>stayed at a shitty as $85 a night hotel right on the beach, not the Delano 
>or whatever.  One day I came back from the conference (or was it the 
>beach?) and Glaude was spinning in the lobby of the hotel.  There were like 
>3 people in there dancing.
>
>One of the best parties I went to was hosted by SF's Panhandle records 
>(RIP) at a little bar called "Blue".  I went back there another time not 
>during WMC and also had a great time.
>
>I was at another party up on the roof of some apartment building hosted by 
>the makers of that VJ product Majix (sp?) and DJ Dan was spinning.  There 
>were maybe 200 industry people there and it was free.
>
>THe boat party we sponsored rocked with Juan Atkins, DJ Dan, and Pete Tong 
>spinning.
>
>I saw Kevin Saunderson and Derrick May at Red, and they played the best 
>music I've ever heard of any type.  OK, I had VIP for this party but it 
>didn't matter.  Saunderson and everyone else was out on the dance floor.
>
>I remember strolling down Collins and dropping into some record store at 
>1:30 AM and having to fight to get at the bins it was so crowded.  And lets 
>not forget the sandwhicherie sandwhiches.
>
>I was also there at Level when some very expensive video equipment 
>"disappeared" but that's another story.
>
>I'm not saying the Miami thing isn't in effect, and yeah you probably can't 
>wear Pumas to most of parties, its just that there is more to WMC than just 
>see and be seen.
>
>Id' go again in an instant if I could.
>
>IMO. YMMV.
>

Subject: RE: [sfraves] Summer Music Conference & the new :code tv

Yeah the whole point is that for that week we take over South Beach, =
I've
never been turned away at the door for dress or appearance, and I've =
never
been to parties with thicker vibes than the best at WMC.  When you're in =
a
packed spot, with one of the best DJs in the world playing, and every =
single
person in there knows and appreciates how well they're playing, that =
vibe
just bounces right back to the DJ and you get some of the most amazing =
sets
and dj/crowd vibes feeding off each other, it can be unbelievable.  =
Never
experienced anything like it anywhere else.

And I don't think SMC will ever get as big as WMC, we simply don't have =
the
venues available to us, especially in such close proximity.

A

No, you haven't.  Straight up.  It is a completely different vibe when =
you
are in a room with 100-200 people, and every single one of them is a =
serious
dj/producer/record label owner that has been in the industry for years =
upon
years and deems it worthy to spend a lot of time and money to make it =
out to
Miami, and every single one of them is going nuts like they're fanboys =
again
to DJ after DJ that rank in the best of the world.  It is a completely
different level of appreciation and crowd reaction specifically because =
of
the crowd involved.  Not to devalue your experiences, it is just a =
different
thing altogether.

Again, I have been to a number of events over my 10+ years on listening =
to
and playing this music, and seen a number of thick ass vibes at parties, =
and
I'm not saying every year or party at WMC is like that by a long shot, =
but
when the stars align, nothing comes close to touching the pinnacle of a =
few
of the best parties I've been to at WMC.

are raided, shot, or even taken away, never to be heard from again.  =20
crazy?  well, i hope so.


>
> The thing about conspiracy theories is that they are rarely very =20
> good theories.  They can't be proven or disproven.  That's sort of =20
> the point actually.  With respect to 9/11, how can you ever prove =20
> it either way?  That is, describe to me the procedure by which the =20
> correct decision about what actually happened could be reliably and =20=

> repeatably made by independent testers.  I'l argue that no such =20
> procedure exists.  We'll just never know.  Therefore, it ends up =20
> just being a contest of opinions.   Which does not mean its not =20
> true of course.

here's a common definition of the word conspiracy:

conspiracy |k=C9=99n=CB=88spir=C9=99s=C4=93| |k=C9=99n=CB=8Csp=C9=AAr=C9=99=
si| |k=C9=99n=CB=8Csp=C9=AAr=C9=99si|
noun ( pl. -cies)
a secret plan by a group to do something unlawful or harmful : a =20
conspiracy to destroy the government. See note at plot .
=E2=80=A2 the action of plotting or conspiring : they were cleared of =20=

conspiracy to pervert the course of justice.

this not only applies to the unofficial theories, but also the =20
official story that 9/11 was a conspiracy carried out by 19 hijackers =20=

carrying box cutters, of which half have been found to actually be =20
still alive as admitted by mainstream media outlets.  so you're =20
right, conspiracy theories are hard to prove, but the official story =20
is getting harder and harder to believe by each passing day.

his malthusian apocalyptic theories on global warming, which isn't =20

to be caused more than anything else by the sun, and may reach its =20
peak in about 7 years.

anyway ...

Native Instruments at Digiworld

   Dear jason hemmenway,

   Native Instruments would like to invite you to this year's
   DigiWorld, Digidesign's annual music instrument and
   technology event. Taking place in San Francisco from
   October 6th =96 7th, this special 2-day event gives you
   the opportunity to explore all the Native Instruments
   products integrated into a Pro Tools setup, with a
   particular emphasis on all the new releases: MASSIVE,
   BATTERY 3, ABSYNTH 4 and FM8.

   The Digiworld is being held in San Francisco's Mezzanine
   venue on 444 Jessie Street and doors are open daily from
   10am-4pm. Attendance is free and it's just a quick
   10-minute walk from the concurring AES Conference.
-> http://www.native-instruments.com/digiworld.info

   Best regards,

   Your Native Instruments Team

In celebration of the release of the Digital D&A music label and the culmination of the First Annual Summer Music Conference in San Francisco, we gather to showcase the continuing digital revolution in electronic dance music. Featuring such labels as TEKELEC (UK) Fevah US, Vibrance Recordings, and our new baby, Digital D&A. In association with Beatport, and with support from Spundae, Fevah, and Vibrance, D&A Music proudly brings you... 
 
DIGITAL AGE 
Thursday, September 28th, 2006 
 
Main Room (Tech Trance): 
 
Ali Wilson (TEKELEC, Quality Trax, UK) 
Ali Wilson has consistently risen in the UK dance scene, although he had his humble beginnings in Hard Dance with releases on such labels as Flashpoint, Freezing Point, Quality Trax, 5AM, and many others; he has now switched lanes and now runs and promotes his own label, TEKELEC. Tekelec sees constant pushes from Carl Cox, Marvo V, and Sander Van Doorn among others. While he does showcase the pioneering of the tech trance scene as a whole, also come to watch this greatly talented DJ display the works! 
 
With D&A Residents: 
Durty (D&A Music, Nocturnalism, Evolution, djDurty.com) 
Viticus (D&A Music, Quality trax) 
Dekota (D&A Music) 
 
Side Room: 
 
Alain Octavo (Spundae, alainoctavo.com) 
Alain Octavo is a master of his craft, and he is as diverse as it gets. Which explains why he is the go-to opener for all of Spundae's A-List headliners. 
 
Andrew Innes (Beatport, Fevah US) 
Andrew is the most interesting of DJs. Now in Chicago, he originally hails from New Zealand, and has done everything from catch wild animals in the America southwest to fishing in Antarctica for Padagonian Tooth Fish. He also is one half of the "Fevah Bros." and founder of Fevah US, and the huge download giant, Beatport.com. He will most likely drop an illegal amount of funky electro house on this parade! 
 
Carlos Alfonzo (Vibrance Recordings, House Nation, BR) 
DJ PM (Evolution, Ear Wacks) 
 
$10 on the door 
 
FREE With your SMC All access Pass before 11:00pm, $2 After 11pm 
This Event is 21+ 
 
Located at: 
Club Hide 
280 Seventh St. 
San Francisco 
 
Doors open 9pm-2am

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Temple

Content-Type: text/plain; charset=ISO-8859-1; format=flowed
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit
Content-Disposition: inline

Ah, I was not there when it was DV8...

The set up is really open on the main floor, high ceilings...very white &
clean...there are booths/banquettes set up in the back and on the
side...they were playing house in this area...they have a decent size bar,
but $30 minimum on credit cards.  I only drank beer, and I didn't pay for
it, so no clue on pricing for that.  They had dancers on an upper level that
you could see through a shade (silhouettes) - very sexy...

The lower level is much darker, lower ceilings, very 'temple' feeling...they
have stone columns & I don't know if you remember the James Bond game from
Nintendo64...but there is a basement/temple level from that game which
totally reminded of the space I was in last night.  Lots of space for
dancing.  Behind the DJ booth there were a plethora of black leather couches
- quite comfortable,and the music was just as loud there as it was in front
of the booth.

Off to the side of the main room downstairs, there is a small chill room,
with brighter, cleaner lighting (reminiscent of upstairs decor) - large bar,
lots of seating...but quiet music which I could barely hear over the din.

The sound in the large rooms was actually quite good.  Now, keep in mind, I
was pretty drunk when I arrived, but it was rich, with a good balance of
treble & bass.  It sounded better than Mighty does a lot of the time.

A plus for me was bathrooms are on both floors...

Security was a non-issue...just checked IDs and directed you inside.

I did feel under-dressed though in my jeans & sweater...it was a sexy
outfit, but not dressy at all.  A lot of the girls were in skirts &
non-denim items...good looking crowd though, and less obnoxious than the
crowds I experience at Ruby Skye.

I preferred the lighting & atmosphere in the lower level - they had this
cool green LASER light going on by the DJ booth down there. It just a had a
much darker, dirtier feel...

I enjoyed the music in the lower level more than on the main level.  It was
just your standard house up there, hard to go wrong, but nothing
mind-blowing.  Downstairs I heard some electro...I really do love
electro...it got me moving a bit.  Embarassing though, I have no idea who
was spinning.  (I was entertaining a broker for dinner and consumed a bit
too much alcohol prior to heading over...complete accident ending up there)

I personally think the sound at Ruby Skye is better...but the atmosphere at
Temple is a bit cooler...Sound is the most important part of the equation.
I love to dance, and if it sounds like crap, it's hard to want to dance.
The only reason I compared it to Mighty is because that is a place I
frequent and I have had some nights where the sound is amazing there (this
past weekend) and nights where it has been AWFUL (think thanksgiving last
year - during lee coombs set - the sound went out - WTF).

I may head out there again to check ShyFX this weekend though...

> Ah, I was not there when it was DV8...
>
> The set up is really open on the main floor, high ceilings...very white &
> clean...there are booths/banquettes set up in the back and on the
> side...they were playing house in this area...they have a decent size bar,
> but $30 minimum on credit cards.  I only drank beer, and I didn't pay for
> it, so no clue on pricing for that.  They had dancers on an upper level that
> you could see through a shade (silhouettes) - very sexy...
>
> The lower level is much darker, lower ceilings, very 'temple'
> feeling...they have stone columns & I don't know if you remember the James
> Bond game from Nintendo64...but there is a basement/temple level from that
> game which totally reminded of the space I was in last night.  Lots of space
> for dancing.  Behind the DJ booth there were a plethora of black leather
> couches - quite comfortable,and the music was just as loud there as it was
> in front of the booth.
>
> Off to the side of the main room downstairs, there is a small chill room,
> with brighter, cleaner lighting (reminiscent of upstairs decor) - large bar,
> lots of seating...but quiet music which I could barely hear over the din.
>
> The sound in the large rooms was actually quite good.  Now, keep in mind,
> I was pretty drunk when I arrived, but it was rich, with a good balance of
> treble & bass.  It sounded better than Mighty does a lot of the time.
>
> A plus for me was bathrooms are on both floors...
>
> Security was a non-issue...just checked IDs and directed you inside.
>
> I did feel under-dressed though in my jeans & sweater...it was a sexy
> outfit, but not dressy at all.  A lot of the girls were in skirts &
> non-denim items...good looking crowd though, and less obnoxious than the
> crowds I experience at Ruby Skye.
>
> I preferred the lighting & atmosphere in the lower level - they had this
> cool green LASER light going on by the DJ booth down there. It just a had a
> much darker, dirtier feel...
>
>

that was a great description of the place for those of us who haven't been yet. thank you! it sounds like this venue has places to sit and hang out (couches, chill area, etc.) which i really like. i think that's one major thing that ruby skye is missing. it seems like all of the places to sit are roped off every time i go there. i'd be willing to brave that crowd more often if there were couches to retreat to once in a while.

> ----- Original Message ----
> From: Jessie 
> To: "dangrsmind@yahoo.com" 
> Cc: SFR 
> Sent: Friday, September 29, 2006 9:04:24 AM
> Subject: Re: [sfraves] Temple
>
> Ah, I was not there when it was DV8...
>
> The set up is really open on the main floor, high ceilings...very white &
> clean...there are booths/banquettes set up in the back and on the
> side...they were playing house in this area...they have a decent size bar,
> but $30 minimum on credit cards.  I only drank beer, and I didn't pay for
> it, so no clue on pricing for that.  They had dancers on an upper level that
> you could see through a shade (silhouettes) - very sexy...
>
> The lower level is much darker, lower ceilings, very 'temple'
> feeling...they have stone columns & I don't know if you remember the James
> Bond game from Nintendo64...but there is a basement/temple level from that
> game which totally reminded of the space I was in last night.  Lots of space
> for dancing.  Behind the DJ booth there were a plethora of black leather
> couches - quite comfortable,and the music was just as loud there as it was
> in front of the booth.
>
> Off to the side of the main room downstairs, there is a small chill room,
> with brighter, cleaner lighting (reminiscent of upstairs decor) - large bar,
> lots of seating...but quiet music which I could barely hear over the din.
>
> The sound in the large rooms was actually quite good.  Now, keep in mind,
> I was pretty drunk when I arrived, but it was rich, with a good balance of
> treble & bass.  It sounded better than Mighty does a lot of the time.
>
> A plus for me was bathrooms are on both floors...
>
> Security was a non-issue...just checked IDs and directed you inside.
>
> I did feel under-dressed though in my jeans & sweater...it was a sexy
> outfit, but not dressy at all.  A lot of the girls were in skirts &
> non-denim items...good looking crowd though, and less obnoxious than the
> crowds I experience at Ruby Skye.
>
> I preferred the lighting & atmosphere in the lower level - they had this
> cool green LASER light going on by the DJ booth down there. It just a had a
> much darker, dirtier feel...
>
>
> On 9/29/06, dangrsmind@yahoo.com  wrote:
> >
> > Well give us a review then!
> >
> > The Temple is the old DV8, an ancient venue where some of us oldsters
> > spent some time way back when.  Maybe some one can remind me what the name
> > of the famous reggae night was...
> >
> > "I felt under-dressed in my denim"
> >
> > Well right there that ain't the old DV8...
> >
> > I don't think it was possible to under dress at the DV8, well maybe if
> > you were naked...
> >
> > Peace,
> >
> > Peter
> >

Dunno to be honest - normally, or rather, some of the time - the sound has 
been either tinny and lacking in mids, or farty, and totally lacking in 
proper mids and highs - what us muscian folk call "muddy" sound.

This past weekedn it was clear as a bell, loud, but very warm and 
responsive. Like a good system once it's been warmed up and the subs are 
nice and flexed out.

Ex as in ex-boyfriend, but not ex-husband right?  Were you co-habitating?  =
For how long?=0A=0AIs he claiming the items are his?=0A=0AIf he isn't, you =
can probably go there with a police officer and ask nicely for him to give =
them back.  =0A=0AIf he claims the items are his, but they aren't, you'd ha=
ve to sue him in small claims court for the value of the items.  Obviosusly=
 not having receipts, or any evidecne of ownership, lowers your chance of s=
uccess there but then he doesn't have receipts either so, its going tobe yo=
ur word against his.  If anyone was with you when you bought the items they=
  might be able to appear as a witness on your behalf.  It costs < $50 to f=
ile in small claims court, and you can sue for up to $5000.  The best metho=
d of success is to be completely honest, don't over value the items in ques=
tion or make anything up, and let your opponent dance around and lie and ap=
pear dishonest.  The judges in small claims are generally good at telling w=
ho is lying, and so if you aren't and he is your chances are increased.  Of=
 course, even if you win there's the non-trival matter of collecting the mo=
ney.  You can't squeeze blood from a stone.  And no guarantee you'll get th=
e items themselves back at all via this route.=0A=0AFirst step, contact the=
 local police and tell them the situation.  See if they will send an office=
r to accompany you to get your items.  Be on your best behavior and no matt=
er what happens don't get in a fight, verbal or otherwise, with the ex.  Ag=
ain let the ex be the one causing a problem if there is going to be a probl=
em.  You can use a police report as evidence in your small claims case.  If=
 it has been a long time since you were co-habitating,you might be out of l=
uck as the police won't help and the court will wonder why you didn't try t=
o get your stuff right away.=0A=0ABeen there and done that...=0A=0APeter=0A=

The DV8 was the home of one of the first "rave" parties  -- Pete Avila's Osmosis. I still have little liquid filled tubes advertising the event. 

Last event I attended there was, I believe, "Release the Queen."  Sex room and all:)  In fact, there used to be rooms with a view where one was encouraged to have public sex.

No bottle service in those days.  No VIP memberships.  Dress was creative costuming made from thrift stores.

Keith Haring did a room there, that was fortunately removed and preserved when the club closed.

I'll second the recommendation for the police. They can actually be  
quite helpful in situations like this, but its kinda a dice role.  
They could be helpful or they could be not. if you go over there with  
an officer and your ex says the stuff is not yours its highly likely  
that the officer will be able to tell that he is lying and will be  
interested in helping you resolve the situation without taking it any  
further. (i.e. courts, etc.)

Nate


On Sep 29, 2006, at 1:41 PM, dangrsmind@yahoo.com wrote:

> Ex as in ex-boyfriend, but not ex-husband right?  Were you co- 
> habitating?  For how long?
>
> Is he claiming the items are his?
>
> If he isn't, you can probably go there with a police officer and  
> ask nicely for him to give them back.
>
> If he claims the items are his, but they aren't, you'd have to sue  
> him in small claims court for the value of the items.  Obviosusly  
> not having receipts, or any evidecne of ownership, lowers your  
> chance of success there but then he doesn't have receipts either  
> so, its going tobe your word against his.  If anyone was with you  
> when you bought the items they  might be able to appear as a  
> witness on your behalf.  It costs < $50 to file in small claims  
> court, and you can sue for up to $5000.  The best method of success  
> is to be completely honest, don't over value the items in question  
> or make anything up, and let your opponent dance around and lie and  
> appear dishonest.  The judges in small claims are generally good at  
> telling who is lying, and so if you aren't and he is your chances  
> are increased.  Of course, even if you win there's the non-trival  
> matter of collecting the money.  You can't squeeze blood from a  
> stone.  And no guarantee you'll get the items themselves back at  
> all via this route.
>
> First step, contact the local police and tell them the situation.   
> See if they will send an officer to accompany you to get your  
> items.  Be on your best behavior and no matter what happens don't  
> get in a fight, verbal or otherwise, with the ex.  Again let the ex  
> be the one causing a problem if there is going to be a problem.   
> You can use a police report as evidence in your small claims case.   
> If it has been a long time since you were co-habitating,you might  
> be out of luck as the police won't help and the court will wonder  
> why you didn't try to get your stuff right away.
>
> Been there and done that...
>
> Peter

--- dangrsmind@yahoo.com wrote:

> Ex as in ex-boyfriend, but not ex-husband right? 
> Were you co-habitating?  For how long?
> 
> Is he claiming the items are his?
> 
> If he isn't, you can probably go there with a police
> officer and ask nicely for him to give them back.  
> 
> If he claims the items are his, but they aren't,
> you'd have to sue him in small claims court for the
> value of the items.  Obviosusly not having receipts,
> or any evidecne of ownership, lowers your chance of
> success there but then he doesn't have receipts
> either so, its going tobe your word against his.  If
> anyone was with you when you bought the items they 
> might be able to appear as a witness on your behalf.
>  It costs < $50 to file in small claims court, and
> you can sue for up to $5000.  The best method of
> success is to be completely honest, don't over value
> the items in question or make anything up, and let
> your opponent dance around and lie and appear
> dishonest.  The judges in small claims are generally
> good at telling who is lying, and so if you aren't
> and he is your chances are increased.  Of course,
> even if you win there's the non-trival matter of
> collecting the money.  You can't squeeze blood from
> a stone.  And no guarantee you'll get the items
> themselves back at all via this route.
> 
> First step, contact the local police and tell them
> the situation.  See if they will send an officer to
> accompany you to get your items.  Be on your best
> behavior and no matter what happens don't get in a
> fight, verbal or otherwise, with the ex.  Again let
> the ex be the one causing a problem if there is
> going to be a problem.  You can use a police report
> as evidence in your small claims case.  If it has
> been a long time since you were co-habitating,you
> might be out of luck as the police won't help and
> the court will wonder why you didn't try to get your
> stuff right away.
> 
> Been there and done that...
>

up.  Its best if you have a written inventory of the items you are claiming=
 are yours in as much detail as possible.  If there are any unique items th=
at he might not be able to describe in detail, make sure those are on the l=
ist. and described carefully.  If some of the items are obviously not his (=
i.e. womens clothing) even better.  This might be obvious, but sInce you ar=
e involving law enforcement you shouldn't list illegal or even questionable=
 items.  The police won't help you retrieve your bong even if its a giant h=
and blown glass baby worth hundreds of dollars.  =0A=0AIf you can't find ou=
t where he lives, you might be SOL.=0A=0AAnd Steve's point is well taken,  =

a couple of years ago when my exhubby was cheating on me, the woman who left her records with him while they were having the affair then decided to get them back when the affair was over it took awhile like almost 8 months, because him being the punkass that he was didnt want to give them back...she showed up at his work with a police officer, since she didnt have our address, she eventually got the records back from him...hope this helps..

> --- dangrsmind@yahoo.com wrote:
>
> > Ex as in ex-boyfriend, but not ex-husband right?
> > Were you co-habitating?  For how long?
> >
> > Is he claiming the items are his?
> >
> > If he isn't, you can probably go there with a police
> > officer and ask nicely for him to give them back.
> >
> > If he claims the items are his, but they aren't,
> > you'd have to sue him in small claims court for the
> > value of the items.  Obviosusly not having receipts,
> > or any evidecne of ownership, lowers your chance of
> > success there but then he doesn't have receipts
> > either so, its going tobe your word against his.  If
> > anyone was with you when you bought the items they
> > might be able to appear as a witness on your behalf.
> >  It costs < $50 to file in small claims court, and
> > you can sue for up to $5000.  The best method of
> > success is to be completely honest, don't over value
> > the items in question or make anything up, and let
> > your opponent dance around and lie and appear
> > dishonest.  The judges in small claims are generally
> > good at telling who is lying, and so if you aren't
> > and he is your chances are increased.  Of course,
> > even if you win there's the non-trival matter of
> > collecting the money.  You can't squeeze blood from
> > a stone.  And no guarantee you'll get the items
> > themselves back at all via this route.
> >
> > First step, contact the local police and tell them
> > the situation.  See if they will send an officer to
> > accompany you to get your items.  Be on your best
> > behavior and no matter what happens don't get in a
> > fight, verbal or otherwise, with the ex.  Again let
> > the ex be the one causing a problem if there is
> > going to be a problem.  You can use a police report
> > as evidence in your small claims case.  If it has
> > been a long time since you were co-habitating,you
> > might be out of luck as the police won't help and
> > the court will wonder why you didn't try to get your
> > stuff right away.
> >
> > Been there and done that...
> >
> > Peter

> > > If he isn't, you can probably go there with a
> police
> > > officer and ask nicely for him to give them
> back.
> > >
> > > If he claims the items are his, but they aren't,
> > > you'd have to sue him in small claims court for
> the
> > > value of the items.  Obviosusly not having
> receipts,
> > > or any evidecne of ownership, lowers your chance
> of
> > > success there but then he doesn't have receipts
> > > either so, its going tobe your word against his.
>  If
> > > anyone was with you when you bought the items
> they
> > > might be able to appear as a witness on your
> behalf.
> > >  It costs < $50 to file in small claims court,
> and
> > > you can sue for up to $5000.  The best method of
> > > success is to be completely honest, don't over
> value
> > > the items in question or make anything up, and
> let
> > > your opponent dance around and lie and appear
> > > dishonest.  The judges in small claims are
> generally
> > > good at telling who is lying, and so if you
> aren't
> > > and he is your chances are increased.  Of
> course,
> > > even if you win there's the non-trival matter of
> > > collecting the money.  You can't squeeze blood
> from
> > > a stone.  And no guarantee you'll get the items
> > > themselves back at all via this route.
> > >
> > > First step, contact the local police and tell
> them
> > > the situation.  See if they will send an officer
> to
> > > accompany you to get your items.  Be on your
> best
> > > behavior and no matter what happens don't get in
> a
> > > fight, verbal or otherwise, with the ex.  Again
> let
> > > the ex be the one causing a problem if there is
> > > going to be a problem.  You can use a police
> report
> > > as evidence in your small claims case.  If it
> has
> > > been a long time since you were
> co-habitating,you
> > > might be out of luck as the police won't help
> and
> > > the court will wonder why you didn't try to get
> your
> > > stuff right away.
> > >
> > > Been there and done that...
> > >
> > > Peter
> > >
> > > ----- Original Message ----
> > > From: Delia <velouria83@yahoo.com>

--- dangrsmind@yahoo.com wrote:

> I don't know if an officer would go to his
> workplace...I'd guess not.
> 
> You are going to need to contact the local police at
> the location where the ex is...preferably near his
> home when he is there waiting for you to show up. 
> Its best if you have a written inventory of the
> items you are claiming are yours in as much detail
> as possible.  If there are any unique items that he
> might not be able to describe in detail, make sure
> those are on the list. and described carefully.  If
> some of the items are obviously not his (i.e. womens
> clothing) even better.  This might be obvious, but
> sInce you are involving law enforcement you
> shouldn't list illegal or even questionable items. 
> The police won't help you retrieve your bong even if
> its a giant hand blown glass baby worth hundreds of
> dollars.  
> 
> If you can't find out where he lives, you might be
> SOL.
> 
> And Steve's point is well taken,  Think carefully
> about whether the hassle is worth it before going
> down this route.  Involving the police can become a
> big deal, and you give up control once you involve
> them.  But if you need to get the stuff back and the
> ex isn't giving the items up there's probably no
> other safe or legal way to get them.
> 
> Peace,
> 
> Peter

Subject: Re: [sfraves] nrr legal advice

I know I was a bit sarcastic in my llast response...
and this is more a course of action response ...

1) contact the guy and tell him you would like to get
your stuff. Ask him a closed end question like ... "I
have time monday or tuesday evening to come get my
records, which night is better for you?"

2) Wait for respoonse. If negative, tell him, " This
has gotten a bit ridiculous.The only recourse I have
to retrieve my stuff is to ask for a police escort to
aid me in the process. They do this daily, and without
question to help take the tension out of domestic
situations. I think it would suck for both of us to
have to get the police involved, so can we just meet
at  Starbucks and you can give me my records back. Or
better yet, our mutaul friend X can come by and save
us both the hassle of seeing eachother."

3) If this does not work, let him kow that the only
recourse you now have is the police action.
Furthermore, since you do not know where he now lives,
you would have to come to his work in order to
confront him. And although you think that is a
terrible idea, because it would embarress him and make
him look like a criminal to his co-workers, it is the
only chopice he is giving you.

Hope that helps.

E

> > > Ex as in ex-boyfriend, but not ex-husband right?
> > > Were you co-habitating?  For how long?
> > >
> > > Is he claiming the items are his?
> > >
> > > If he isn't, you can probably go there with a
> police
> > > officer and ask nicely for him to give them
> back.
> > >
> > > If he claims the items are his, but they aren't,
> > > you'd have to sue him in small claims court for
> the
> > > value of the items.  Obviosusly not having
> receipts,
> > > or any evidecne of ownership, lowers your chance
> of
> > > success there but then he doesn't have receipts
> > > either so, its going tobe your word against his.
>  If
> > > anyone was with you when you bought the items
> they
> > > might be able to appear as a witness on your
> behalf.
> > >  It costs < $50 to file in small claims court,
> and
> > > you can sue for up to $5000.  The best method of
> > > success is to be completely honest, don't over
> value
> > > the items in question or make anything up, and
> let
> > > your opponent dance around and lie and appear
> > > dishonest.  The judges in small claims are
> generally
> > > good at telling who is lying, and so if you
> aren't
> > > and he is your chances are increased.  Of
> course,
> > > even if you win there's the non-trival matter of
> > > collecting the money.  You can't squeeze blood
> from
> > > a stone.  And no guarantee you'll get the items
> > > themselves back at all via this route.
> > >
> > > First step, contact the local police and tell
> them
> > > the situation.  See if they will send an officer
> to
> > > accompany you to get your items.  Be on your
> best
> > > behavior and no matter what happens don't get in
> a
> > > fight, verbal or otherwise, with the ex.  Again
> let
> > > the ex be the one causing a problem if there is
> > > going to be a problem.  You can use a police
> report
> > > as evidence in your small claims case.  If it
> has
> > > been a long time since you were
> co-habitating,you
> > > might be out of luck as the police won't help
> and
> > > the court will wonder why you didn't try to get
> your
> > > stuff right away.
> > >
> > > Been there and done that...

> to retrieve my stuff is to ask for a police escort to
> aid me in the process. They do this daily, and without
> question to help take the tension out of domestic
> situations. I think it would suck for both of us to
> have to get the police involved, so can we just meet
> at  Starbucks and you can give me my records back. Or
> better yet, our mutaul friend X can come by and save
> us both the hassle of seeing eachother."
>
> 3) If this does not work, let him kow that the only
> recourse you now have is the police action.
> Furthermore, since you do not know where he now lives,
> you would have to come to his work in order to
> confront him. And although you think that is a
> terrible idea, because it would embarress him and make
> him look like a criminal to his co-workers, it is the
> only chopice he is giving you.
>
